# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cell-biology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cell-biology/cell-biology] The study of cells is performed using microscopy techniques, cell culture, and cell fractionation.
[src:cell-biology/cell-biology] These are used for research into how cells function, which ultimately gives insight into larger organisms.
[src:cell-biology/cell-biology] Knowing the components of cells and how cells work is fundamental to all biological sciences and is essential for research in biomedical fields such as cancer, and other diseases.
[src:cell-biology/cell-biology] Research in cell biology is interconnected to other fields such as genetics, molecular genetics, molecular biology, medical microbiology, immunology, and cytochemistry.
[src:cell-biology/cell-biology] Cells were first seen in 17th-century Europe with the invention of the compound microscope.
[src:cell-biology/cell-biology] In 1665, Robert Hooke referred to the building blocks of all living organisms as "cells" (published in *Micrographia*) after looking at a piece of cork and observing a structure reminiscent of monastic cells; however, the cells were dead.
[src:cell-biology/cell-biology] They gave no indication to the actual overall components of a cell.
[src:cell-biology/cell-biology] A few years later, in 1674, Anton Van Leeuwenhoek was the first to analyze live cells in his examination of algae.
[src:cell-biology/cell-biology] Many years later, in 1831, Robert Brown discovered the nucleus.
[src:cell-biology/cell-biology] All of this preceded the cell theory which states that all living things are made up of cells and that cells are organisms' functional and structural units.
[src:cell-biology/cell-biology] This was ultimately concluded by plant scientist Matthias Schleiden and animal scientist Theodor Schwann in 1838, who viewed live cells in plant and animal tissue, respectively.
[src:cell-biology/cell-biology] 19 years later, Rudolf Virchow further contributed to the cell theory, adding that all cells come from the division of pre-existing cells.
[src:cell-biology/cell-biology] Viruses are not considered in cell biology – they lack the characteristics of a living cell and instead are studied in the microbiology subclass of virology.
[src:cell-biology/cell-biology] Cell biology research looks at different ways to culture and manipulate cells outside of a living body to further research in human anatomy and physiology, and to derive medications.
[src:cell-biology/cell-biology] The techniques by which cells are studied have evolved.
[src:cell-biology/cell-biology] Due to advancements in microscopy, techniques and technology have allowed scientists to hold a better understanding of the structure and function of cells.
[src:cell-biology/cell-biology] The scientific branch that studies and diagnoses diseases on the cellular level is called cytopathology.
[src:cell-biology/cell-biology] Cytopathology is generally used on samples of free cells or tissue fragments, in contrast to the pathology branch of histopathology, which studies whole tissues.
[src:cell-biology/cell-biology] Cytopathology is commonly used to investigate diseases involving a wide range of body sites, often to aid in the diagnosis of cancer but also in the diagnosis of some infectious diseases and other inflammatory conditions.
[src:cell-biology/cell-biology] For example, a common application of cytopathology is the Pap smear, a screening test used to detect cervical cancer, and precancerous cervical lesions that may lead to cervical cancer.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The **cell cycle**, or **cell-division cycle**, is the sequence of events that take place in a cell and lead to its division into two daughter cells.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] These events include the growth of the cell, duplication of its DNA (DNA replication) and some of its organelles, and subsequently the partitioning of its cytoplasm, chromosomes and other components into two daughter cells in a process called cell division.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] In eukaryotic cells (having a cell nucleus) including animal, plant, fungal, and protist cells, the cell cycle is divided into two main stages: interphase, and the M phase that includes mitosis and cytokinesis.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] During interphase, the cell grows, accumulating nutrients needed for mitosis, and replicates its DNA and some of its organelles.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Its successive stages differ in their specialized biochemical processes, preparing the cell for initiation of the cell's division, but are not usually morphologically distinguishable.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] During the M phase, the replicated chromosomes, organelles, and cytoplasm separate into two new daughter cells.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] To ensure the proper replication of cellular components and division, cell cycle checkpoints follow each of the key stages of the cycle, controlling whether the cell progresses to the next.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] In cells without nuclei (the prokaryotes: bacteria and archaea), the cell cycle is divided into the B, C, and D periods.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The B period extends from the end of cell division to the beginning of DNA replication.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] DNA replication occurs during the C period.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The D period refers to the stage between the end of DNA replication and the splitting of the bacterial cell into two daughter cells.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] In single-celled organisms, a single cell-division cycle is how the organism reproduces.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] After cell division, each of the daughter cells begins the interphase of a new cell cycle.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The eukaryotic cell cycle consists of four distinct phases: G1 phase, S phase (synthesis), G2 phase (collectively known as interphase) and M phase (mitosis and cytokinesis).
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] M phase is itself composed of two tightly coupled processes: mitosis, in which the cell's nucleus divides, and cytokinesis, in which the cell's cytoplasm and cell membrane divides forming two daughter cells.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Activation of each phase is dependent on the proper progression and completion of the previous one.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Cells that have temporarily or reversibly stopped dividing are said to have entered a state of quiescence known as G0 phase or *resting phase*.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] G0 is a resting phase where the cell has left the cycle and has stopped dividing.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Non-proliferative (non-dividing) cells in multicellular eukaryotes generally enter the quiescent G0 state from G1 and may remain quiescent for long periods of time, possibly indefinitely (as is often the case for neurons).
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] This is very common for cells that are fully differentiated.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Some cells enter the G0 phase semi-permanently and are considered post-mitotic, e.g., some liver, kidney, and stomach cells.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Many cells do not enter G0 and continue to divide throughout an organism's life, e.g., epithelial cells.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The word "post-mitotic" is sometimes used to refer to both quiescent and senescent cells.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Cellular senescence occurs in response to DNA damage and external stress and usually constitutes an arrest in G1.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Cellular senescence may make a cell's progeny nonviable; it is often a biochemical alternative to the self-destruction of such a damaged cell by apoptosis.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Interphase represents the phase between two successive M phases.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Interphase is a series of changes that takes place in a newly formed cell and its nucleus before it becomes capable of division again.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] It is also called preparatory phase or intermitosis.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Typically interphase lasts for at least 91% of the total time required for the cell cycle.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Interphase proceeds in three stages, G1, S, and G2, followed by the cycle of mitosis and cytokinesis.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The cell's nuclear DNA contents are duplicated during S phase.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The first phase within interphase, from the end of the previous M phase until the beginning of DNA synthesis, is called G1 (G indicating *gap*).
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] During this phase, the biosynthetic activities of the cell, which are considerably slowed down during M phase, resume at a high rate.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The duration of G1 is highly variable, even among different cells of the same species.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] In this phase, the cell increases its supply of proteins, increases the number of organelles (such as mitochondria, ribosomes), and grows in size.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The deciding point is called check point (Restriction point).
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] This check point is called the restriction point or START and is regulated by G1/S cyclins, which cause transition from G1 to S phase.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Passage through the G1 check point commits the cell to division.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The ensuing S phase starts when DNA synthesis commences; when it is complete, all of the chromosomes have been replicated, i.e., each chromosome consists of two sister chromatids.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Thus, during this phase, the amount of DNA in the cell has doubled, though the ploidy and number of chromosomes are unchanged.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Rates of RNA transcription and protein synthesis are very low during this phase.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] An exception to this is histone production, most of which occurs during the S phase.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] G2 phase occurs after DNA replication and is a period of protein synthesis and rapid cell growth to prepare the cell for mitosis.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] During this phase microtubules begin to reorganize to form a spindle (preprophase).
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Before proceeding to mitotic phase, cells must be checked at the G2 checkpoint for any DNA damage within the chromosomes.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The G2 checkpoint is mainly regulated by the tumor protein p53.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] If the DNA is damaged, p53 will either repair the DNA or trigger the apoptosis of the cell.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] If p53 is dysfunctional or mutated, cells with damaged DNA may continue through the cell cycle, leading to the development of cancer.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The relatively brief *M phase* consists of nuclear division (karyokinesis) and division of cytoplasm (cytokinesis).
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] M phase is complex and highly regulated.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The sequence of events is divided into phases, corresponding to the completion of one set of activities and the start of the next.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Mitosis is the process by which a eukaryotic cell separates the chromosomes in its cell nucleus into two identical sets in two nuclei.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] During the process of mitosis the pairs of chromosomes condense (chromosome condensation) and attach to microtubules that pull the sister chromatids to opposite sides of the cell.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Mitosis occurs exclusively in eukaryotic cells, but occurs in different ways in different species.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] For example, animal cells undergo an "open" mitosis, where the nuclear envelope breaks down before the chromosomes separate, while fungi such as *Aspergillus nidulans* and *Saccharomyces cerevisiae* (yeast) undergo a "closed" mitosis, where chromosomes divide within an intact cell nucleus.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Mitosis is immediately followed by cytokinesis, which divides the nuclei, cytoplasm, organelles and cell membrane into two cells containing roughly equal shares of these cellular components.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Cytokinesis occurs differently in plant and animal cells.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] While the cell membrane forms a groove that gradually deepens to separate the cytoplasm in animal cells, a cell plate is formed to separate it in plant cells.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The position of the cell plate is determined by the position of a preprophase band of microtubules and actin filaments.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Mitosis and cytokinesis together define the division of the parent cell into two daughter cells, genetically identical to each other and to their parent cell.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] This accounts for approximately 10% of the cell cycle.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Because cytokinesis usually occurs in conjunction with mitosis, "mitosis" is often used interchangeably with "M phase".
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] However, there are many cells where mitosis and cytokinesis occur separately, forming single cells with multiple nuclei in a process called endoreplication.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] This occurs most notably among the fungi and slime molds, but is found in various groups.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Even in animals, cytokinesis and mitosis may occur independently, for instance during certain stages of fruit fly embryonic development.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Errors in mitosis can result in cell death through apoptosis or cause mutations that may lead to cancer.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Regulation of the cell cycle involves processes crucial to the survival of a cell, including the detection and repair of genetic damage as well as the prevention of uncontrolled cell division.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The molecular events that control the cell cycle are ordered and directional; that is, each process occurs in a sequential fashion and it is impossible to "reverse" the cycle.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Two key classes of regulatory molecules, cyclins and cyclin-dependent kinases (CDKs), determine a cell's progress through the cell cycle.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Nurse won the 2001 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for their discovery of these central molecules.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Many of the genes encoding cyclins and CDKs are conserved among all eukaryotes, but in general, more complex organisms have more elaborate cell cycle control systems that incorporate more individual components.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Many of the relevant genes were first identified by studying yeast, especially *Saccharomyces cerevisiae*; genetic nomenclature in yeast dubs many of these genes *cdc* (for "cell division cycle") followed by an identifying number, e.g.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Cyclins form the regulatory subunits and CDKs the catalytic subunits of an activated heterodimer; cyclins have no catalytic activity and CDKs are inactive in the absence of a partner cyclin.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] When activated by a bound cyclin, CDKs perform a common biochemical reaction called phosphorylation that activates or inactivates target proteins to orchestrate coordinated entry into the next phase of the cell cycle.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Different cyclin-CDK combinations determine the downstream proteins targeted.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] CDKs are constitutively expressed in cells whereas cyclins are synthesised at specific stages of the cell cycle, in response to various molecular signals.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Upon receiving a pro-mitotic extracellular signal, G1 cyclin-CDK complexes become active to prepare the cell for S phase, promoting the expression of transcription factors that in turn promote the expression of S cyclins and of enzymes required for DNA replication.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The G1 cyclin-CDK complexes also promote the degradation of molecules that function as S phase inhibitors by targeting them for ubiquitination.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Once a protein has been ubiquitinated, it is targeted for proteolytic degradation by the proteasome.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Results from a study of E2F transcriptional dynamics at the single-cell level argue that the role of G1 cyclin-CDK activities, in particular cyclin D-CDK4/6, is to tune the timing rather than the commitment of cell cycle entry.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Active S cyclin-CDK complexes phosphorylate proteins that make up the pre-replication complexes assembled during G1 phase on DNA replication origins.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The phosphorylation serves two purposes: to activate each already-assembled pre-replication complex, and to prevent new complexes from forming.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] This ensures that every portion of the cell's genome will be replicated once and only once.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The reason for prevention of gaps in replication is fairly clear, because daughter cells that are missing all or part of crucial genes will die.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] However, for reasons related to gene copy number effects, possession of extra copies of certain genes is also deleterious to the daughter cells.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Mitotic cyclin-CDK complexes, which are synthesized but inactivated during S and G2 phases, promote the initiation of mitosis by stimulating downstream proteins involved in chromosome condensation and mitotic spindle assembly.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] A critical complex activated during this process is a ubiquitin ligase known as the anaphase-promoting complex (APC), which promotes degradation of structural proteins associated with the chromosomal kinetochore.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] APC also targets the mitotic cyclins for degradation, ensuring that telophase and cytokinesis can proceed.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Cyclin D is the first cyclin produced in the cells that enter the cell cycle, in response to extracellular signals (e.g. growth factors).
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Cyclin D levels stay low in resting cells that are not proliferating.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Additionally, CDK4/6 and CDK2 are also inactive because CDK4/6 are bound by INK4 family members (e.g., p16), limiting kinase activity.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Meanwhile, CDK2 complexes are inhibited by the CIP/KIP proteins such as p21 and p27, When it is time for a cell to enter the cell cycle, which is triggered by a mitogenic stimuli, levels of cyclin D increase.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] In response to this trigger, cyclin D binds to existing CDK4/6, forming the active cyclin D-CDK4/6 complex.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Cyclin D-CDK4/6 complexes in turn mono-phosphorylates the retinoblastoma susceptibility protein (Rb) to pRb.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The un-phosphorylated Rb tumour suppressor functions in inducing cell cycle exit and maintaining G0 arrest (senescence).
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] In the last few decades, a model has been widely accepted whereby pRB proteins are inactivated by cyclin D-Cdk4/6-mediated phosphorylation.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Rb has 14+ potential phosphorylation sites.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Cyclin D-Cdk 4/6 progressively phosphorylates Rb to hyperphosphorylated state, which triggers dissociation of pRB–E2F complexes, thereby inducing G1/S cell cycle gene expression and progression into S phase.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] In early G1 cells, mono-phosphorylated Rb exists as 14 different isoforms, one of each has distinct E2F binding affinity.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Rb has been found to associate with hundreds of different proteins and the idea that different mono-phosphorylated Rb isoforms have different protein partners was very appealing.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] A later report confirmed that mono-phosphorylation controls Rb's association with other proteins and generates functional distinct forms of Rb.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] All different mono-phosphorylated Rb isoforms inhibit E2F transcriptional program and are able to arrest cells in G1-phase.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Different mono-phosphorylated forms of Rb have distinct transcriptional outputs that are extended beyond E2F regulation.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] In general, the binding of pRb to E2F inhibits the E2F target gene expression of certain G1/S and S transition genes including E-type cyclins.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The partial phosphorylation of Rb de-represses the Rb-mediated suppression of E2F target gene expression, begins the expression of cyclin E.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The molecular mechanism that causes the cell switched to cyclin E activation is currently not known, but as cyclin E levels rise, the active cyclin E-CDK2 complex is formed, bringing Rb to be inactivated by hyper-phosphorylation.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Hyperphosphorylated Rb is completely dissociated from E2F, enabling further expression of a wide range of E2F target genes are required for driving cells to proceed into S phase [1].
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] It has been identified that cyclin D-Cdk4/6 binds to a C-terminal alpha-helix region of Rb that is only distinguishable to cyclin D rather than other cyclins, cyclin E, A and B.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] This observation based on the structural analysis of Rb phosphorylation supports that Rb is phosphorylated in a different level through multiple Cyclin-Cdk complexes.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] This also makes feasible the current model of a simultaneous switch-like inactivation of all mono-phosphorylated Rb isoforms through one type of Rb hyper-phosphorylation mechanism.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] In addition, mutational analysis of the cyclin D- Cdk 4/6 specific Rb C-terminal helix shows that disruptions of cyclin D-Cdk 4/6 binding to Rb prevents Rb phosphorylation, arrests cells in G1, and bolsters Rb's functions in tumor suppressor.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] This cyclin-Cdk driven cell cycle transitional mechanism governs a cell committed to the cell cycle that allows cell proliferation.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] A cancerous cell growth often accompanies with deregulation of Cyclin D-Cdk 4/6 activity.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The hyperphosphorylated Rb dissociates from the E2F/DP1/Rb complex (which was bound to the E2F responsive genes, effectively "blocking" them from transcription), activating E2F.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Activation of E2F results in transcription of various genes like cyclin E, cyclin A, DNA polymerase, thymidine kinase, etc.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Cyclin E thus produced binds to CDK2, forming the cyclin E-CDK2 complex, which pushes the cell from G1 to S phase (G1/S, which initiates the G2/M transition).
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Cyclin B-cdk1 complex activation causes breakdown of nuclear envelope and initiation of prophase, and subsequently, its deactivation causes the cell to exit mitosis.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] A quantitative study of E2F transcriptional dynamics at the single-cell level by using engineered fluorescent reporter cells provided a quantitative framework for understanding the control logic of cell cycle entry, challenging the canonical textbook model.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Genes that regulate the amplitude of E2F accumulation, such as Myc, determine the commitment in cell cycle and S phase entry.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] G1 cyclin-CDK activities are not the driver of cell cycle entry.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Instead, they primarily tune the timing of E2F increase, thereby modulating the pace of cell cycle progression.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Two families of genes, the *cip/kip* (*CDK interacting protein/Kinase inhibitory protein*) family and the INK4a/ARF (*In*hibitor of *K*inase 4/*A*lternative *R*eading *F*rame) family, prevent the progression of the cell cycle.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Because these genes are instrumental in prevention of tumor formation, they are known as tumor suppressors.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The ***cip/kip* family** includes the genes p21, p27 and p57.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] They halt the cell cycle in G1 phase by binding to and inactivating cyclin-CDK complexes. p21 is activated by p53 (which, in turn, is triggered by DNA damage e.g. due to radiation). p27 is activated by Transforming Growth Factor β (TGF β), a growth inhibitor.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The **INK4a/ARF family** includes p16INK4a, which binds to CDK4 and arrests the cell cycle in G1 phase, and p14ARF which prevents p53 degradation.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Synthetic inhibitors of Cdc25 could also be useful for the arrest of cell cycle and therefore be useful as antineoplastic and anticancer agents.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Many human cancers possess the hyper-activated Cdk 4/6 activities.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Given the observations of cyclin D-Cdk 4/6 functions, inhibition of Cdk 4/6 should result in preventing a malignant tumor from proliferating.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Consequently, scientists have tried to invent the synthetic Cdk4/6 inhibitor as Cdk4/6 has been characterized to be a therapeutic target for anti-tumor effectiveness.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Three Cdk4/6 inhibitors – palbociclib, ribociclib, and abemaciclib – currently received FDA approval for clinical use to treat advanced-stage or metastatic, hormone-receptor-positive (HR-positive, HR+), HER2-negative (HER2-) breast cancer.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] For example, palbociclib is an orally active CDK4/6 inhibitor which has demonstrated improved outcomes for ER-positive/HER2-negative advanced breast cancer.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The main side effect is neutropenia which can be managed by dose reduction.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Cdk4/6 targeted therapy will only treat cancer types where Rb is expressed.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Cancer cells with loss of Rb have primary resistance to Cdk4/6 inhibitors.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Current evidence suggests that a semi-autonomous transcriptional network acts in concert with the CDK-cyclin machinery to regulate the cell cycle.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Several gene expression studies in *Saccharomyces cerevisiae* have identified 800–1200 genes that change expression over the course of the cell cycle.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] They are transcribed at high levels at specific points in the cell cycle, and remain at lower levels throughout the rest of the cycle.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] While the set of identified genes differs between studies due to the computational methods and criteria used to identify them, each study indicates that a large portion of yeast genes are temporally regulated.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Many periodically expressed genes are driven by transcription factors that are also periodically expressed.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] One screen of single-gene knockouts identified 48 transcription factors (about 20% of all non-essential transcription factors) that show cell cycle progression defects.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The expression profiles of these transcription factors are driven by the transcription factors that peak in the prior phase, and computational models have shown that a CDK-autonomous network of these transcription factors is sufficient to produce steady-state oscillations in gene expression).
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Experimental evidence also suggests that gene expression can oscillate with the period seen in dividing wild-type cells independently of the CDK machinery.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Orlando *et al.* used microarrays to measure the expression of a set of 1,271 genes that they identified as periodic in both wild type cells and cells lacking all S-phase and mitotic cyclins (*clb1,2,3,4,5,6*).
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Of the 1,271 genes assayed, 882 continued to be expressed in the cyclin-deficient cells at the same time as in the wild type cells, despite the fact that the cyclin-deficient cells arrest at the border between G1 and S phase.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] However, 833 of the genes assayed changed behavior between the wild type and mutant cells, indicating that these genes are likely directly or indirectly regulated by the CDK-cyclin machinery.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Some genes that continued to be expressed on time in the mutant cells were also expressed at different levels in the mutant and wild type cells.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] These findings suggest that while the transcriptional network may oscillate independently of the CDK-cyclin oscillator, they are coupled in a manner that requires both to ensure the proper timing of cell cycle events.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Other work indicates that phosphorylation, a post-translational modification, of cell cycle transcription factors by Cdk1 may alter the localization or activity of the transcription factors in order to tightly control timing of target genes.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] While oscillatory transcription plays a key role in the progression of the yeast cell cycle, the CDK-cyclin machinery operates independently in the early embryonic cell cycle.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Before the midblastula transition, zygotic transcription does not occur and all needed proteins, such as the B-type cyclins, are translated from maternally loaded mRNA.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] This confirms previous predictions from mathematical modeling of a global causal coordination between DNA replication origin activity and mRNA expression, and shows that mathematical modeling of DNA microarray data can be used to correctly predict previously unknown biological modes of regulation.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Cell cycle checkpoints are used by the cell to monitor and regulate the progress of the cell cycle.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Checkpoints prevent cell cycle progression at specific points, allowing verification of necessary phase processes and repair of DNA damage.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The cell cannot proceed to the next phase until checkpoint requirements have been met.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Checkpoints typically consist of a network of regulatory proteins that monitor and dictate the progression of the cell through the different stages of the cell cycle.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] It is estimated that in normal human cells about 1% of single-strand DNA damages are converted to about 50 endogenous DNA double-strand breaks per cell per cell cycle.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Although such double-strand breaks are usually repaired with high fidelity, errors in their repair are considered to contribute significantly to the rate of cancer in humans.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] There are several checkpoints to ensure that damaged or incomplete DNA is not passed on to daughter cells.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Three main checkpoints exist: the G1/S checkpoint, the G2/M checkpoint and the metaphase (mitotic) checkpoint.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Another checkpoint is the Go checkpoint, in which the cells are checked for maturity.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] If the cells are not ready, they do not pass this checkpoint and will be discarded from dividing.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] G1/S transition is a rate-limiting step in the cell cycle and is also known as restriction point.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] This is where the cell checks whether it has enough raw materials to fully replicate its DNA (nucleotide bases, DNA synthase, chromatin, etc.).
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] An unhealthy or malnourished cell will get stuck at this checkpoint.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The G2/M checkpoint is where the cell ensures that it has enough cytoplasm and phospholipids for two daughter cells.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] But sometimes more importantly, it checks to see if it is the right time to replicate.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] There are some situations where many cells need to all replicate simultaneously (for example, a growing embryo should have a symmetric cell distribution until it reaches the mid-blastula transition).
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] This is done by controlling the G2/M checkpoint.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The metaphase checkpoint is a fairly minor checkpoint because a cell in metaphase has already committed to undergo mitosis.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Nevertheless, it is important because in this checkpoint, the cell checks to ensure that the spindle has formed and that all of the chromosomes are aligned at the spindle equator before anaphase begins.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] While these are the three "main" checkpoints, not all cells have to pass through each of these checkpoints in this order to replicate.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Many types of cancer are caused by mutations that allow the cells to speed through the various checkpoints or even skip them altogether, going from the S to M to S phase almost consecutively.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Because these cells have lost their checkpoints, any DNA mutations that may have occurred are disregarded and passed on to the daughter cells.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] This is one reason why cancer cells have a tendency to exponentially acquire mutations.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Aside from cancer cells, many fully differentiated cell types no longer replicate so they leave the cell cycle and stay in G0 until their death, thus removing the need for cellular checkpoints.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] An alternative model of the cell cycle response to DNA damage has also been proposed, known as the postreplication checkpoint.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Checkpoint regulation plays an important role in an organism's development.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] In sexual reproduction, when egg fertilization occurs, when the sperm binds to the egg, it releases signalling factors that notify the egg that it has been fertilized.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Among other things, this induces the now fertilized oocyte to return from its previously dormant G0 state back into the cell cycle and on to mitotic replication and division.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] p53 plays an important role in triggering the control mechanisms at both G1/S and G2/M checkpoints.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] In addition to p53, checkpoint regulators are being heavily researched for their roles in cancer growth and proliferation.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Pioneering work by Atsushi Miyawaki and coworkers developed the fluorescent ubiquitination-based cell cycle indicator (FUCCI), which enables fluorescence imaging of the cell cycle.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Originally, a green fluorescent protein, mAG, was fused to hGem(1/110) and an orange fluorescent protein (mKO2) was fused to hCdt1(30/120).
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Note, these fusions are fragments that contain a nuclear localization signal and ubiquitination sites for degradation, but are not functional proteins.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The green fluorescent protein is made during the S, G2, or M phase and degraded during the G0 or G1 phase, while the orange fluorescent protein is made during the G0 or G1 phase and destroyed during the S, G2, or M phase.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] A far-red and near-infrared FUCCI was developed using a cyanobacteria-derived fluorescent protein (smURFP) and a bacteriophytochrome-derived fluorescent protein (movie found at this link).
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Several modifications have been made to the original FUCCI system to improve its usability in several in vitro systems and model organisms.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] These advancements have increased the sensitivity and accuracy of cell cycle phase detection, enabling more precise assessments of cellular proliferation.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] A disregulation of the cell cycle components may lead to tumor formation.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] As mentioned above, when some genes like the cell cycle inhibitors, RB, p53 etc. mutate, they may cause the cell to multiply uncontrollably, forming a tumor.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Although the duration of cell cycle in tumor cells is equal to or longer than that of normal cell cycle, the proportion of cells that are in active cell division (versus quiescent cells in G0 phase) in tumors is much higher than that in normal tissue.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Thus there is a net increase in cell number as the number of cells that die by apoptosis or senescence remains the same.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The cells which are actively undergoing cell cycle are targeted in cancer therapy as the DNA is relatively exposed during cell division and hence susceptible to damage by drugs or radiation.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] This fact is made use of in cancer treatment; by a process known as debulking, a significant mass of the tumor is removed which pushes a significant number of the remaining tumor cells from G0 to G1 phase (due to increased availability of nutrients, oxygen, growth factors etc.).
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Radiation or chemotherapy following the debulking procedure kills these cells which have newly entered the cell cycle.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The fastest cycling mammalian cells in culture, crypt cells in the intestinal epithelium, have a cycle time as short as 9 to 10 hours.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Stem cells in resting mouse skin may have a cycle time of more than 200 hours.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Most of this difference is due to the varying length of G1, the most variable phase of the cycle.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] In general, cells are most radiosensitive in late M and G2 phases and most resistant in late S phase.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] For cells with a longer cell cycle time and a significantly long G1 phase, there is a second peak of resistance late in G1.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The pattern of resistance and sensitivity correlates with the level of sulfhydryl compounds in the cell.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Sulfhydryls are natural substances that protect cells from radiation damage and tend to be at their highest levels in S and at their lowest near mitosis.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Homologous recombination (HR) is an accurate process for repairing DNA double-strand breaks.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] HR is nearly absent in G1 phase, is most active in S phase, and declines in G2/M.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Non-homologous end joining, a less accurate and more mutagenic process for repairing double strand breaks, is active throughout the cell cycle.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Most prokaryotes (bacteria and archaea) reproduce by binary fission.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Despite not having a cell nucleus and the complex systems for managing the nuclear envelope, prokaryotes still need to schedule its DNA replication and cell division properly in their own cell cycle mechanisms.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The bacterial cell cycle is regulated very differently from the eukaryotic one.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] A phase can be reached *before* the previous phase is completed.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] For example, in very fast-growing bacteria, a new round of DNA replication can begin before the cell division is even complete.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] In bacteria that use FtsZ for division, chromosomal DNA replication happens concurrently with the assembly of the FtsZ ring and the broader divisome.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] DNA replication is required for properly positioning the FtsZ ring at one end of the cell; when DNA replication is prevented but FtsZ production is allowed to continue, the ring appears at the center of the cell.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The archaeal cell cycle is quite comparable to the eukaryotic cell cycle, except there is no singular position for a resting (G0) phase and two separate cell division phases.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] There is a great deal of diversity in cell cycle organization among archaea.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The TACK archaea (which include *Sulfolobus*) have a well-ordered cell cycle, with *Sulfolobus* usually arrested at the G2 phase during the stationary phase or by external stimuli.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The Euryarchaeota tend to be more relaxed with many polyploid cells, but *Methanothermobacter thermautotrophicus* stands out for having strictly diploid and tetraploid phases.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Like in eukaryotes, proteolysis (espeicially the proteosome) is central to cell cycle progression, as is DNA replication.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Transcription of cell division proteins and DNA replication machinery exhibit a cyclic pattern in sync with the cell cycle, but it is not totally clear what transcription factors (TFs) are causing this effect.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Most species contain bacterial-style TFs that target specific genes, with some ribbon-helix-helix (RHH) TFs especially implicated in generating the cycle.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Some species contain homologs of eukaryotic cell cycle-related transcription factors (TFB2 in TACK, E2F in Asgard).
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The cell cycle must duplicate all cellular constituents and equally partition them into two daughter cells.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Many constituents, such as proteins and ribosomes, are produced continuously throughout the cell cycle (except during M-phase).
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] However, the chromosomes and other associated elements like MTOCs, are duplicated just once during the cell cycle.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] A central component of the cell cycle is its ability to coordinate the continuous and periodic duplications of different cellular elements, which evolved with the formation of the genome.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The pre-cellular environment contained functional and self-replicating RNAs.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] All RNA concentrations depended on the concentrations of other RNAs that might be helping or hindering the gathering of resources.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] In this environment, growth was simply the continuous production of RNAs.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] These pre-cellular structures would have had to contend with parasitic RNAs, issues of inheritance, and copy-number control of specific RNAs.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Partitioning "genomic" RNA from "functional" RNA helped solve these problems.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The fusion of multiple RNAs into a genome gave a template from which functional RNAs were cleaved.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Now, parasitic RNAs would have to incorporate themselves into the genome, a much greater barrier, in order to survive.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Controlling the copy number of genomic RNA also allowed RNA concentration to be determined through synthesis rates and RNA half-lives, instead of competition.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Separating the duplication of genomic RNAs from the generation of functional RNAs allowed for much greater duplication fidelity of genomic RNAs without compromising the production of functional RNAs.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Finally, the replacement of genomic RNA with DNA, which is a more stable molecule, allowed for larger genomes.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The transition from self-catalysis enzyme synthesis to genome-directed enzyme synthesis was a critical step in cell evolution, and had lasting implications on the cell cycle, which must regulate functional synthesis and genomic duplication in very different ways.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Cell-cycle progression is controlled by the oscillating concentrations of different cyclins and the resulting molecular interactions from the various cyclin-dependent kinases (CDKs).
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] In yeast, just one CDK (Cdc28 in *S. cerevisiae* and Cdc2 in *S. pombe*) controls the cell cycle.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] However, in animals, whole families of CDKs have evolved.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Cdk1 controls entry to mitosis and Cdk2, Cdk4, and Cdk6 regulate entry into S phase.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Despite the evolution of the CDK family in animals, these proteins have related or redundant functions.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] For example, *cdk2 cdk4 cdk6* triple knockout mice cells can still progress through the basic cell cycle.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] *cdk1* knockouts are lethal, which suggests an ancestral CDK1-type kinase ultimately controlling the cell cycle.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The G1/S checkpoint is the point at which the cell commits to division through the cell cycle.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Complex regulatory networks lead to the G1/S transition decision.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Across opisthokonts, there are both highly diverged protein sequences as well as strikingly similar network topologies.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Entry into S-phase in both yeast and animals is controlled by the levels of two opposing regulators.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The networks regulating these transcription factors are double-negative feedback loops and positive feedback loops in both yeast and animals.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Additional regulation of the regulatory network for the G1/S checkpoint in yeast and animals includes the phosphorylation/de-phosphorylation of CDK-cyclin complexes.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] The sum of these regulatory networks creates a hysteretic and bistable scheme, despite the specific proteins being highly diverged.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] For yeast, Whi5 must be suppressed by Cln3 phosphorylation for SBF to be expressed, while in animals Rb must be suppressed by the Cdk4/6-cyclin D complex for E2F to be expressed.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Both Rb and Whi5 inhibit transcript through the recruitment of histone deacetylase proteins to promoters.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Both proteins additionally have multiple CDK phosphorylation sites through which they are inhibited.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] However, these proteins share no sequence similarity.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Studies in *A. thaliana* extend our knowledge of the G1/S transition across eukaryotes as a whole.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] Plants also share a number of conserved network features with opisthokonts, and many plant regulators have direct animal homologs.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] For example, plants also need to suppress Rb for E2F translation in the network.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] These conserved elements of the plant and animal cell cycles may be ancestral in eukaryotes.
[src:cell-biology/cell-cycle] While yeast share a conserved network topology with plants and animals, the highly diverged nature of yeast regulators suggests possible rapid evolution along the yeast lineage.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The **cell membrane** (also known as the **plasma membrane** or **cytoplasmic membrane**, and historically referred to as the **plasmalemma**) is a semipermeable biological membrane that separates and protects the interior of a cell from the outside environment (the extracellular space).
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The cell membrane is a lipid bilayer, usually consisting of phospholipids and glycolipids; eukaryotes and some archaea typically have sterols (such as cholesterol in animals) interspersed between them as well, maintaining appropriate membrane fluidity at various temperatures.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The membrane also contains membrane proteins, including integral proteins that span the membrane and serve as transporters, and peripheral proteins that attach to the surface of the cell membrane, acting as enzymes to facilitate interaction with the cell's environment.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Glycolipids embedded in the outer lipid layer serve a similar purpose.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The cell membrane controls the movement of substances in and out of a cell, being selectively permeable to ions and organic molecules.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] In the field of synthetic biology, cell membranes can be artificially reassembled.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Robert Hooke's discovery of cells in 1665 led to the proposal of the cell theory.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Initially it was believed that all cells contained a hard cell wall since only plant cells could be observed at the time.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Microscopists focused on the cell wall for well over 150 years until advances in microscopy were made.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] In the early 19th century, cells were recognized as being separate entities, unconnected, and bound by individual cell walls after it was found that plant cells could be separated.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] This theory extended to include animal cells to suggest a universal mechanism for cell protection and development.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] By the second half of the 19th century, microscopy was still not advanced enough to make a distinction between cell membranes and cell walls.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] However, some microscopists correctly identified at this time that while invisible, it could be inferred that cell membranes existed in animal cells due to intracellular movement of components internally but not externally and that membranes were not the equivalent of a plant cell wall.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] It was also inferred that cell membranes were not vital components to all cells.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Many refuted the existence of a cell membrane still towards the end of the 19th century.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] In 1890, a revision to the cell theory stated that cell membranes existed, but were merely secondary structures.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] It was not until later studies with osmosis and permeability that cell membranes gained more recognition.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] In 1895, Ernest Overton proposed that cell membranes were made of lipids.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The lipid bilayer hypothesis, proposed in 1925 by Gorter and Grendel, created speculation in the description of the cell membrane bilayer structure based on crystallographic studies and soap bubble observations.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] In an attempt to accept or reject the hypothesis, researchers measured membrane thickness.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] These researchers extracted the lipid from human red blood cells and measured the amount of surface area the lipid would cover when spread over the surface of the water.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Since mature mammalian red blood cells lack both nuclei and cytoplasmic organelles, the plasma membrane is the only lipid-containing structure in the cell.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Consequently, all of the lipids extracted from the cells can be assumed to have resided in the cells' plasma membranes.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The ratio of the surface area of water covered by the extracted lipid to the surface area calculated for the red blood cells from which the lipid was 2:1(approx) and they concluded that the plasma membrane contains a lipid bilayer.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] In 1925 it was determined by Fricke that the thickness of erythrocyte and yeast cell membranes ranged between 3.3 and 4 nm, a thickness compatible with a lipid monolayer.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The choice of the dielectric constant used in these studies was called into question but future tests could not disprove the results of the initial experiment.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Independently, the leptoscope was invented in order to measure very thin membranes by comparing the intensity of light reflected from a sample to the intensity of a membrane standard of known thickness.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The instrument could resolve thicknesses that depended on pH measurements and the presence of membrane proteins that ranged from 8.6 to 23.2 nm, with the lower measurements supporting the lipid bilayer hypothesis.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Later in the 1930s, the membrane structure model developed in general agreement to be the paucimolecular model of Davson and Danielli (1935).
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] This model was based on studies of surface tension between oils and echinoderm eggs.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Since the surface tension values appeared to be much lower than would be expected for an oil–water interface, it was assumed that some substance was responsible for lowering the interfacial tensions in the surface of cells.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] It was suggested that a lipid bilayer was in between two thin protein layers.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The paucimolecular model immediately became popular and it dominated cell membrane studies for the following 30 years, until it became rivaled by the fluid mosaic model of Singer and Nicolson (1972).
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Despite the numerous models of the cell membrane proposed prior to the fluid mosaic model, it remains the primary archetype for the cell membrane long after its inception in the 1970s.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The fluid mosaic model not only provided an accurate representation of membrane mechanics, it enhanced the study of hydrophobic forces, which would later develop into an essential descriptive limitation to describe biological macromolecules.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] For many centuries, the scientists cited disagreed with the significance of the structure they were seeing as the cell membrane.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] For almost two centuries, the membranes were seen but mostly disregarded as an important structure with cellular function.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] It was not until the 20th century that the significance of the cell membrane as it was acknowledged.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Finally, two scientists Gorter and Grendel (1925) made the discovery that the membrane is "lipid-based".
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] From this, they furthered the idea that this structure would have to be in a formation that mimicked layers.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Once studied further, it was found by comparing the sum of the cell surfaces and the surfaces of the lipids, a 2:1 ratio was estimated; thus, providing the first basis of the bilayer structure known today.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] This discovery initiated many new studies that arose globally within various fields of scientific studies, confirming that the structure and functions of the cell membrane are widely accepted.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Some authors who did not believe that there was a functional permeable boundary at the surface of the cell preferred to use the term plasmalemma (coined by Mast, 1924) for the external region of the cell.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Cell membranes contain a variety of biological molecules, notably lipids and proteins.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Composition is not set, but constantly changing for fluidity and changes in the environment, even fluctuating during different stages of cell development.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Specifically, the amount of cholesterol in human primary neuron cell membrane changes, and this change in composition affects fluidity throughout development stages.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The cell membrane consists of three classes of amphipathic lipids: phospholipids, glycolipids, and sterols.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The amount of each depends upon the type of cell, but in the majority of cases phospholipids are the most abundant, often contributing for over 50% of all lipids in plasma membranes.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Glycolipids only account for a minute amount of about 2% and sterols make up the rest.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] In red blood cell studies, 30% of the plasma membrane is lipid.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] However, for the majority of eukaryotic cells, the composition of plasma membranes is about half lipids and half proteins by weight.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The fatty chains in phospholipids and glycolipids usually contain an even number of carbon atoms, typically between 16 and 20.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The 16- and 18-carbon fatty acids are the most common.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Fatty acids may be saturated or unsaturated, with the configuration of the double bonds nearly always "cis".
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The length and the degree of unsaturation of fatty acid chains have a profound effect on membrane fluidity as unsaturated lipids create a kink, preventing the fatty acids from packing together as tightly, thus decreasing the melting temperature (increasing the fluidity) of the membrane.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The ability of some organisms to regulate the fluidity of their cell membranes by altering lipid composition is called homeoviscous adaptation.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The entire membrane is held together via non-covalent interaction of hydrophobic tails, however the structure is quite fluid and not fixed rigidly in place.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Under physiological conditions phospholipid molecules in the cell membrane are in the liquid crystalline state.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] It means the lipid molecules are free to diffuse and exhibit rapid lateral diffusion along the layer in which they are present.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] However, the exchange of phospholipid molecules between intracellular and extracellular leaflets of the bilayer is a very slow process.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Lipid rafts and caveolae are examples of cholesterol-enriched microdomains in the cell membrane.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Also, a fraction of the lipid in direct contact with integral membrane proteins, which is tightly bound to the protein surface is called annular lipid shell; it behaves as a part of protein complex.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Cholesterol is normally found dispersed in varying degrees throughout cell membranes, in the irregular spaces between the hydrophobic tails of the membrane lipids, where it confers a stiffening and strengthening effect on the membrane.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Additionally, the amount of cholesterol in biological membranes varies between organisms, cell types, and even in individual cells.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Cholesterol, a major component of plasma membranes, regulates the fluidity of the overall membrane, meaning that cholesterol controls the amount of movement of the various cell membrane components based on its concentrations.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] In high temperatures, cholesterol inhibits the movement of phospholipid fatty acid chains, causing a reduced permeability to small molecules and reduced membrane fluidity.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The opposite is true for the role of cholesterol in cooler temperatures.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Cholesterol production, and thus concentration, is up-regulated (increased) in response to cold temperature.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] At cold temperatures, cholesterol interferes with fatty acid chain interactions.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Acting as antifreeze, cholesterol maintains the fluidity of the membrane.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Cholesterol is more abundant in cold-weather animals than warm-weather animals.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] In plants, which lack cholesterol, other related sterol compounds perform the same function as cholesterol.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Lipid vesicles or liposomes are approximately spherical pockets that are enclosed by a lipid bilayer.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] These structures are used in laboratories to study the effects of chemicals in cells by delivering these chemicals directly to the cell, as well as getting more insight into cell membrane permeability.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Lipid vesicles and liposomes are formed by first suspending a lipid in an aqueous solution then agitating the mixture through sonication, resulting in a vesicle.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Measuring the rate of efflux from the inside of the vesicle to the ambient solution allows researchers to better understand membrane permeability.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Vesicles can be formed with molecules and ions inside the vesicle by forming the vesicle with the desired molecule or ion present in the solution.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Proteins can also be embedded into the membrane through solubilizing the desired proteins in the presence of detergents and attaching them to the phospholipids in which the liposome is formed.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] These provide researchers with a tool to examine various membrane protein functions.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Plasma membranes also contain carbohydrates, predominantly glycoproteins, but with some glycolipids (cerebrosides and gangliosides).
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Carbohydrates are important in the role of cell-cell recognition in eukaryotes; they are located on the surface of the cell where they recognize host cells and share information.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Viruses that bind to cells using these receptors cause an infection.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] For the most part, no glycosylation occurs on membranes within the cell; rather generally glycosylation occurs on the extracellular surface of the plasma membrane.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The glycocalyx is an important feature in all cells, especially epithelia with microvilli.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Recent data suggest the glycocalyx participates in cell adhesion, lymphocyte homing, and many others.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The penultimate sugar is galactose and the terminal sugar is sialic acid, as the sugar backbone is modified in the Golgi apparatus.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Sialic acid carries a negative charge, providing an external barrier to charged particles.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The cell membrane has large content of proteins, typically around 50% of membrane volume These proteins are important for the cell because they are responsible for various biological activities.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Approximately a third of the genes in yeast code specifically for them, and this number is even higher in multicellular organisms.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Membrane proteins consist of three main types: integral proteins, peripheral proteins, and lipid-anchored proteins.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] As shown in the adjacent table, integral proteins are amphipathic transmembrane proteins.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Examples of integral proteins include ion channels, proton pumps, and g-protein coupled receptors.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Ion channels allow inorganic ions such as sodium, potassium, calcium, or chlorine to diffuse down their electrochemical gradient across the lipid bilayer through hydrophilic pores across the membrane.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The electrical behavior of cells (i.e. nerve cells) is controlled by ion channels.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Proton pumps are protein pumps that are embedded in the lipid bilayer that allow protons to travel through the membrane by transferring from one amino acid side chain to another.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Processes such as electron transport and generating ATP use proton pumps.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] A G-protein coupled receptor is a single polypeptide chain that crosses the lipid bilayer seven times responding to signal molecules (i.e. hormones and neurotransmitters).
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] G-protein coupled receptors are used in processes such as cell to cell signaling, the regulation of the production of cAMP, and the regulation of ion channels.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The cell membrane, being exposed to the outside environment, is an important site of cell–cell communication.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] As such, a large variety of protein receptors and identification proteins, such as antigens, are present on the surface of the membrane.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Functions of membrane proteins can also include cell–cell contact, surface recognition, cytoskeleton contact, signaling, enzymatic activity, or transporting substances across the membrane.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Most membrane proteins must be inserted in some way into the membrane.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] For this to occur, an N-terminus "signal sequence" of amino acids directs proteins to the endoplasmic reticulum, which inserts the proteins into a lipid bilayer.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Once inserted, the proteins are then transported to their final destination in vesicles, where the vesicle fuses with the target membrane.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The cell membrane surrounds the cytoplasm of living cells, physically separating the intracellular components from the extracellular environment.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The cell membrane also plays a role in anchoring the cytoskeleton to provide shape to the cell, and in attaching to the extracellular matrix and other cells to hold them together to form tissues.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Fungi, bacteria, most archaea, and plants also have a cell wall, which provides a mechanical support to the cell and precludes the passage of larger molecules.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The cell membrane is selectively permeable and able to regulate what enters and exits the cell, thus facilitating the transport of materials needed for survival.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The movement of substances across the membrane can be achieved by either passive transport, occurring without the input of cellular energy, or by active transport, requiring the cell to expend energy in transporting it.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The membrane also maintains the cell potential.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The cell membrane thus works as a selective filter that allows only certain things to come inside or go outside the cell.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Transmembrane protein channels and transporters: Transmembrane proteins extend through the lipid bilayer of the membranes; they function on both sides of the membrane to transport molecules across it.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Nutrients, such as sugars or amino acids, must enter the cell, and certain products of metabolism must leave the cell.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Such molecules can diffuse passively through protein channels such as aquaporins in facilitated diffusion or are pumped across the membrane by transmembrane transporters.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Protein channel proteins, also called *permeases*, are usually quite specific, and they only recognize and transport a limited variety of chemical substances, often limited to a single substance.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Another example of a transmembrane protein is a cell-surface receptor, which allow cell signaling molecules to communicate between cells.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Endocytosis: Endocytosis is the process in which cells absorb molecules by engulfing them.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The plasma membrane creates a small deformation inward, called an invagination, in which the substance to be transported is captured.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] This invagination is caused by proteins on the outside on the cell membrane, acting as receptors and clustering into depressions that eventually promote accumulation of more proteins and lipids on the cytosolic side of the membrane.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The deformation then pinches off from the membrane on the inside of the cell, creating a vesicle containing the captured substance.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Endocytosis is a pathway for internalizing solid particles ("cell eating" or phagocytosis), small molecules and ions ("cell drinking" or pinocytosis), and macromolecules.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Endocytosis requires energy and is thus a form of active transport.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Exocytosis: Just as material can be brought into the cell by invagination and formation of a vesicle, the membrane of a vesicle can be fused with the plasma membrane, extruding its contents to the surrounding medium.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Exocytosis occurs in various cells to remove undigested residues of substances brought in by endocytosis, to secrete substances such as hormones and enzymes, and to transport a substance completely across a cellular barrier.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] In the process of exocytosis, the undigested waste-containing food vacuole or the secretory vesicle budded from Golgi apparatus, is first moved by cytoskeleton from the interior of the cell to the surface.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The vesicle membrane comes in contact with the plasma membrane.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The lipid molecules of the two bilayers rearrange themselves and the two membranes are, thus, fused.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] A passage is formed in the fused membrane and the vesicles discharges its contents outside the cell.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Prokaryotes are divided into two different groups: Archaea and Bacteria, with bacteria dividing further into gram-positive and gram-negative.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Gram-negative bacteria have both a plasma membrane and an outer membrane separated by periplasm; however, other prokaryotes have only a plasma membrane.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] These two membranes differ in many aspects.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The outer membrane of the gram-negative bacteria differs from other prokaryotes due to lipopolysaccharides forming the exterior of the bilayer, and lipoproteins and phospholipids forming the interior.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The outer membrane typically has a porous quality due to membrane proteins such as porins, which are pore-forming proteins.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The inner plasma membrane is also generally symmetric, whereas the outer membrane is asymmetric because of proteins such as the aforementioned.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Also, for the prokaryotic membranes, there are multiple things that can affect the fluidity.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] One of the major factors that can affect the fluidity is fatty acid composition.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] For example, when *Staphylococcus aureus* was grown at 37 °C for 24 h, the membrane exhibited a more fluid state instead of a gel-like state.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] This supports the concept that in higher temperatures, the membrane is more fluid than in colder temperatures.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] When the membrane is becoming more fluid and needs to become more stabilized, it will make longer fatty acid chains or saturated fatty acid chains in order to help stabilize the membrane.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Bacteria are also surrounded by a cell wall composed of peptidoglycan (amino acids and sugars).
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Some eukaryotic cells also have cell walls, but none that are made of peptidoglycan.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The outer membrane of gram negative bacteria is rich in lipopolysaccharides, which are combined poly- or oligosaccharide and saccharolipid that stimulate the cell's natural immunity.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The outer membrane can bleb out into periplasmic protrusions under stress conditions or upon virulence requirements while encountering a host target cell, and thus such blebs may work as virulence organelles.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Bacterial cells provide numerous examples of the diverse ways in which prokaryotic cell membranes are adapted with structures that suit the organism's niche.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] For example, proteins on the surface of certain bacterial cells aid in their gliding motion.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Many gram-negative bacteria have cell membranes which contain ATP-driven protein exporting systems.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] According to the fluid mosaic model of S.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Nicolson (1972), which replaced the earlier model of Davson and Danielli, biological membranes can be considered as a two-dimensional liquid in which lipid and protein molecules diffuse more or less easily.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Although the lipid bilayers that form the basis of the membranes do indeed form two-dimensional liquids by themselves, the plasma membrane also contains a large quantity of proteins, which provide more structure.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Examples of such structures are protein-protein complexes, pickets and fences formed by the actin-based cytoskeleton, and potentially lipid rafts.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Lipid bilayers form through the process of self-assembly.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] This forms a continuous, spherical lipid bilayer.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Hydrophobic interactions (also known as the hydrophobic effect) are the major driving forces in the formation of lipid bilayers.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] An increase in interactions between hydrophobic molecules (causing clustering of hydrophobic regions) allows water molecules to bond more freely with each other, increasing the entropy of the system.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] This complex interaction can include noncovalent interactions such as van der Waals, electrostatic and hydrogen bonds.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Lipid bilayers are generally impermeable to ions and polar molecules.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The arrangement of hydrophilic heads and hydrophobic tails of the lipid bilayer prevent polar solutes (ex. amino acids, nucleic acids, carbohydrates, proteins, and ions) from diffusing across the membrane, but generally allows for the passive diffusion of hydrophobic molecules.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] This affords the cell the ability to control the movement of these substances via transmembrane protein complexes such as pores, channels and gates.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Flippases and scramblases concentrate phosphatidyl serine, which carries a negative charge, on the inner membrane.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Along with NANA, this creates an extra barrier to charged moieties moving through the membrane.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Membranes serve diverse functions in eukaryotic and prokaryotic cells.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] One important role is to regulate the movement of materials into and out of cells.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The phospholipid bilayer structure (fluid mosaic model) with specific membrane proteins accounts for the selective permeability of the membrane and passive and active transport mechanisms.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] In addition, membranes in prokaryotes and in the mitochondria and chloroplasts of eukaryotes facilitate the synthesis of ATP through chemiosmosis.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The **apical membrane** or **luminal membrane** of a polarized cell is the surface of the plasma membrane that faces inward to the lumen.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] This is particularly evident in epithelial and endothelial cells, but also describes other polarized cells, such as neurons.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The **basolateral membrane** or basolateral cell membrane of a polarized cell is the surface of the plasma membrane that forms its basal and lateral surfaces.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] It faces outwards, towards the interstitium, and away from the lumen.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Basolateral membrane is a compound phrase referring to the terms "basal (base) membrane" and "lateral (side) membrane", which, especially in epithelial cells, are identical in composition and activity.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Proteins (such as ion channels and pumps) are free to move from the basal to the lateral surface of the cell or vice versa in accordance with the fluid mosaic model.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Tight junctions join epithelial cells near their apical surface to prevent the migration of proteins from the basolateral membrane to the apical membrane.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The basal and lateral surfaces thus remain roughly equivalent to one another, yet distinct from the apical surface.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The cell membrane can form different types of "supramembrane" structures such as caveolae, postsynaptic densities, podosomes, invadopodia, focal adhesions, and different types of cell junction.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] These structures are usually responsible for cell adhesion, communication, endocytosis and exocytosis.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] They are composed of specific proteins, such as integrins and cadherins.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] They can be visualized by electron microscopy or fluorescence microscopy.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The cytoskeleton is found underlying the cell membrane in the cytoplasm and provides a scaffolding for membrane proteins to anchor to, as well as forming organelles that extend from the cell.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Indeed, cytoskeletal elements interact extensively and intimately with the cell membrane.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Anchoring proteins restricts them to a particular cell surface — for example, the apical surface of epithelial cells that line the vertebrate gut — and limits how far they may diffuse within the bilayer.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The cytoskeleton is able to form appendage-like organelles, such as cilia, which are microtubule-based extensions covered by the cell membrane, and filopodia, which are actin-based extensions.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] These extensions are ensheathed in membrane and project from the surface of the cell in order to sense the external environment and/or make contact with the substrate or other cells.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The apical surfaces of epithelial cells are dense with actin-based finger-like projections known as microvilli, which increase cell surface area and thereby increase the absorption rate of nutrients.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Localized decoupling of the cytoskeleton and cell membrane results in formation of a bleb.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The content of the cell, inside the cell membrane, is composed of numerous membrane-bound organelles, which contribute to the overall function of the cell.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The origin, structure, and function of each organelle leads to a large variation in the cell composition due to the individual uniqueness associated with each organelle.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The cell membrane has different lipid and protein compositions in distinct types of cells and may have therefore specific names for certain cell types.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The permeability of a membrane is the rate of passive diffusion of molecules through the membrane.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] These molecules are known as permeant molecules.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Permeability depends mainly on the electric charge and polarity of the molecule and to a lesser extent the molar mass of the molecule.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] Due to the cell membrane's hydrophobic nature, small electrically neutral molecules pass through the membrane more easily than charged, large ones.
[src:cell-biology/cell-membrane] The inability of charged molecules to pass through the cell membrane results in pH partition of substances throughout the fluid compartments of the body.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The **cell nucleus** (from Latin **nucleus* or *nuculeus** 'kernel, seed'; pl.: **nuclei**) is a membrane-bound organelle found in eukaryotic cells.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Eukaryotic cells usually have a single nucleus, but a few cell types, such as mammalian red blood cells, have no nuclei, and a few others including osteoclasts have many.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The main structures making up the nucleus are the nuclear envelope, a double membrane that encloses the entire organelle and isolates its contents from the cellular cytoplasm; and the nuclear matrix, a network within the nucleus that adds mechanical support.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The cell nucleus contains nearly all of the cell's genome.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Nuclear DNA is often organized into multiple chromosomes – long strands of DNA dotted with various proteins, such as histones, that protect and organize the DNA.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The genes within these chromosomes are structured in such a way to promote cell function.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The nucleus maintains the integrity of genes and controls the activities of the cell by regulating gene expression.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Because the nuclear envelope is impermeable to large molecules, nuclear pores are required to regulate nuclear transport of molecules across the envelope.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The pores cross both nuclear membranes, providing a channel through which larger molecules must be actively transported by carrier proteins while allowing free movement of small molecules and ions.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Movement of large molecules such as proteins and RNA through the pores is required for both gene expression and the maintenance of chromosomes.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Although the interior of the nucleus does not contain any membrane-bound subcompartments, a number of nuclear bodies exist, made up of unique proteins, RNA molecules, and particular parts of the chromosomes.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The best-known of these is the nucleolus, involved in the assembly of ribosomes.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The cell nucleus contains most of the cell's genetic material in the form of multiple linear DNA molecules organized into chromosomes.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Each human cell contains roughly two meters of DNA.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Throughout most of the cell cycle this DNA exists in a DNA-protein complex known as chromatin, while during cell division the chromatin forms the well-defined chromosomes familiar from a karyotype.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] A small portion of the cell's genes are instead located in the mitochondria.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Euchromatin is the less compact DNA form, and contains genes that are frequently expressed by the cell.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The other type, heterochromatin, is the more compact form, and contains DNA that is infrequently transcribed.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] During interphase the chromatin organizes itself into discrete individual patches, called *chromosome territories*.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Active genes, which are generally found in the euchromatic region of the chromosome, tend to be located towards the chromosome's territory boundary.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Antibodies to certain types of chromatin organization, in particular, nucleosomes, have been associated with a number of autoimmune diseases, such as systemic lupus erythematosus.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] These are known as anti-nuclear antibodies (ANA) and have also been observed in concert with multiple sclerosis as part of general immune system dysfunction.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The nucleus contains nearly all of the cell's DNA, surrounded by a network of fibrous intermediate filaments called the nuclear matrix, and is enveloped in a double membrane called the nuclear envelope.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The nuclear envelope separates the fluid inside the nucleus, called the nucleoplasm, from the rest of the cell.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The size of the nucleus is correlated to the size of the cell, and this ratio is reported across a range of cell types and species.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] In eukaryotes the nucleus in many cells typically occupies 10% of the cell volume.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The nucleus is the largest organelle in animal cells.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] In human cells, the diameter of the nucleus is approximately six micrometres (μm).
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The nuclear envelope consists of two membranes, an inner and an outer nuclear membrane, perforated by nuclear pores.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Together, these membranes serve to separate the cell's genetic material from the rest of the cell contents, and allow the nucleus to maintain an environment distinct from the rest of the cell.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Despite their close apposition around much of the nucleus, the two membranes differ substantially in shape and contents.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The inner membrane surrounds the nuclear content, providing its defining edge.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Embedded within the inner membrane, various proteins bind the intermediate filaments that give the nucleus its structure.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The outer membrane encloses the inner membrane, and is continuous with the adjacent endoplasmic reticulum membrane.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] As part of the endoplasmic reticulum membrane, the outer nuclear membrane is studded with ribosomes that are actively translating proteins across membrane.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The space between the two membranes is called the perinuclear space, and is continuous with the endoplasmic reticulum lumen.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] In a mammalian nuclear envelope there are between 3000 and 4000 nuclear pore complexes (NPCs) perforating the envelope.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Each NPC contains an eightfold-symmetric ring-shaped structure at a position where the inner and outer membranes fuse.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The number of NPCs can vary considerably across cell types; small glial cells only have about a few hundred, with large Purkinje cells having around 20,000.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The NPC provides selective transport of molecules between the nucleoplasm and the cytosol.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The nuclear pore complex is composed of approximately thirty different proteins known as nucleoporins.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The pores are about 60–80 million daltons in molecular mass and consist of around 50 (in yeast) to several hundred proteins (in vertebrates).
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The pores are 100 nm in total diameter; however, the gap through which molecules freely diffuse is only about 9 nm wide, due to the presence of regulatory systems within the center of the pore.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] This size selectively allows the passage of small water-soluble molecules while preventing larger molecules, such as nucleic acids and larger proteins, from inappropriately entering or exiting the nucleus.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] These large molecules must be actively transported into the nucleus instead.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Attached to the ring is a structure called the **nuclear basket** that extends into the nucleoplasm, and a series of filamentous extensions that reach into the cytoplasm.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Both structures serve to mediate binding to nuclear transport proteins.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Most proteins, ribosomal subunits, and some RNAs are transported through the pore complexes in a process mediated by a family of transport factors known as karyopherins.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Those karyopherins that mediate movement into the nucleus are also called importins, whereas those that mediate movement out of the nucleus are called exportins.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Most karyopherins interact directly with their cargo, although some use adaptor proteins.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Steroid hormones such as cortisol and aldosterone, as well as other small lipid-soluble molecules involved in intercellular signaling, can diffuse through the cell membrane and into the cytoplasm, where they bind nuclear receptor proteins that are trafficked into the nucleus.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] There they serve as transcription factors when bound to their ligand; in the absence of a ligand, many such receptors function as histone deacetylases that repress gene expression.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] In animal cells, two networks of intermediate filaments provide the nucleus with mechanical support: The nuclear lamina forms an organized meshwork on the internal face of the envelope, while less organized support is provided on the cytosolic face of the envelope.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Both systems provide structural support for the nuclear envelope and anchoring sites for chromosomes and nuclear pores.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The nuclear lamina is composed mostly of lamin proteins.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Like all proteins, lamins are synthesized in the cytoplasm and later transported to the nucleus interior, where they are assembled before being incorporated into the existing network of nuclear lamina.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Lamins found on the cytosolic face of the membrane, such as emerin and nesprin, bind to the cytoskeleton to provide structural support.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Lamins are also found inside the nucleoplasm where they form another regular structure, known as the *nucleoplasmic veil*, that is visible using fluorescence microscopy.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The actual function of the veil is not clear, although it is excluded from the nucleolus and is present during interphase.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Lamin structures that make up the veil, such as LEM3, bind chromatin and disrupting their structure inhibits transcription of protein-coding genes.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Like the components of other intermediate filaments, the lamin monomer contains an alpha-helical domain used by two monomers to coil around each other, forming a dimer structure called a coiled coil.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Two of these dimer structures then join side by side, in an antiparallel arrangement, to form a tetramer called a *protofilament*.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Eight of these protofilaments form a lateral arrangement that is twisted to form a ropelike *filament*.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] These filaments can be assembled or disassembled in a dynamic manner, meaning that changes in the length of the filament depend on the competing rates of filament addition and removal.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Mutations in lamin genes leading to defects in filament assembly cause a group of rare genetic disorders known as *laminopathies*.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The most notable laminopathy is the family of diseases known as progeria, which causes the appearance of premature aging in those with the condition.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The exact mechanism by which the associated biochemical changes give rise to the aged phenotype is not well understood.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The nucleolus is the largest of the discrete densely stained, membraneless structures known as nuclear bodies found in the nucleus.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] It forms around tandem repeats of rDNA, DNA coding for ribosomal RNA (rRNA).
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] These regions are called nucleolar organizer regions (NOR).
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The main roles of the nucleolus are to synthesize rRNA and assemble ribosomes.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The structural cohesion of the nucleolus depends on its activity, as ribosomal assembly in the nucleolus results in the transient association of nucleolar components, facilitating further ribosomal assembly, and hence further association.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] This model is supported by observations that inactivation of rDNA results in intermingling of nucleolar structures.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] In the first step of ribosome assembly, a protein called RNA polymerase I transcribes rDNA, which forms a large pre-rRNA precursor.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] This is cleaved into two large rRNA subunits – 5.8S, and 28S, and a small rRNA subunit 18S.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The transcription, post-transcriptional processing, and assembly of rRNA occurs in the nucleolus, aided by small nucleolar RNA (snoRNA) molecules, some of which are derived from spliced introns from messenger RNAs encoding genes related to ribosomal function.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The assembled ribosomal subunits are the largest structures passed through the nuclear pores.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Transcription of the rDNA occurs either in the FC or at the FC-DFC boundary, and, therefore, when rDNA transcription in the cell is increased, more FCs are detected.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Most of the cleavage and modification of rRNAs occurs in the DFC, while the latter steps involving protein assembly onto the ribosomal subunits occur in the GC.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Speckles are subnuclear structures that are enriched in pre-messenger RNA splicing factors and are located in the interchromatin regions of the nucleoplasm of mammalian cells.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] At the fluorescence-microscope level, they appear as irregular, punctate structures, which vary in size and shape, and when examined by electron microscopy, they are seen as clusters of interchromatin granules.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Speckles are dynamic structures, and both their protein and RNA-protein components can cycle continuously between speckles and other nuclear locations, including active transcription sites.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Speckles can work with p53 as enhancers of gene activity to directly enhance the activity of certain genes.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Moreover, speckle-associating and non-associating p53 gene targets are functionally distinct.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Studies on the composition, structure and behaviour of speckles have provided a model for understanding the functional compartmentalization of the nucleus and the organization of the gene-expression machinery splicing snRNPs and other splicing proteins necessary for pre-mRNA processing.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Because of a cell's changing requirements, the composition and location of these bodies changes according to mRNA transcription and regulation via phosphorylation of specific proteins.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The splicing speckles are also known as nuclear speckles (nuclear specks), splicing factor compartments (SF compartments), interchromatin granule clusters (IGCs), and B snurposomes.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] B snurposomes are found in the amphibian oocyte nuclei and in *Drosophila melanogaster* embryos.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] B snurposomes appear alone or attached to the Cajal bodies in the electron micrographs of the amphibian nuclei.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] A nucleus typically contains between one and ten compact structures called Cajal bodies or coiled bodies (CB), whose diameter measures between 0.2 μm and 2.0 μm depending on the cell type and species.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] When seen under an electron microscope, they resemble balls of tangled thread and are dense foci of distribution for the protein coilin.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] CBs are involved in a number of different roles relating to RNA processing, specifically small nucleolar RNA (snoRNA) and small nuclear RNA (snRNA) maturation, and histone mRNA modification.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Similar to Cajal bodies are Gemini of Cajal bodies, or gems, whose name is derived from the Gemini constellation in reference to their close "twin" relationship with CBs.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Gems are similar in size and shape to CBs, and in fact are virtually indistinguishable under the microscope.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Unlike CBs, gems do not contain small nuclear ribonucleoproteins (snRNPs), but do contain a protein called survival of motor neuron (SMN) whose function relates to snRNP biogenesis.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Gems are believed to assist CBs in snRNP biogenesis, though it has also been suggested from microscopy evidence that CBs and gems are different manifestations of the same structure.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Later ultrastructural studies have shown gems to be twins of Cajal bodies with the difference being in the coilin component; Cajal bodies are SMN positive and coilin positive, and gems are SMN positive and coilin negative.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Beyond the nuclear bodies first described by Santiago Ramón y Cajal above (e.g., nucleolus, nuclear speckles, Cajal bodies) the nucleus contains a number of other nuclear bodies.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] These include polymorphic interphase karyosomal association (PIKA), promyelocytic leukaemia (PML) bodies, and paraspeckles.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Although little is known about a number of these domains, they are significant in that they show that the nucleoplasm is not a uniform mixture, but rather contains organized functional subdomains.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Other subnuclear structures appear as part of abnormal disease processes.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] For example, the presence of small intranuclear rods has been reported in some cases of nemaline myopathy.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] This condition typically results from mutations in actin, and the rods themselves consist of mutant actin as well as other cytoskeletal proteins.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] PIKA domains, or polymorphic interphase karyosomal associations, were first described in microscopy studies in 1991.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Their function remains unclear, though they were not thought to be associated with active DNA replication, transcription, or RNA processing.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] They have been found to often associate with discrete domains defined by dense localization of the transcription factor PTF, which promotes transcription of small nuclear RNA (snRNA).
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Promyelocytic leukemia protein (PML-nuclear bodies) are spherical bodies found scattered throughout the nucleoplasm, measuring around 0.1–1.0 μm.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] They are known by a number of other names, including nuclear domain 10 (ND10), Kremer bodies, and PML oncogenic domains.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] PML-nuclear bodies are named after one of their major components, the promyelocytic leukemia protein (PML).
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] They are often seen in the nucleus in association with Cajal bodies and cleavage bodies.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Pml-/- mice, which are unable to create PML-nuclear bodies, develop normally without obvious ill effects, showing that PML-nuclear bodies are not required for most essential biological processes.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Discovered by Fox et al. in 2002, paraspeckles are irregularly shaped compartments in the interchromatin space of the nucleus.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] First documented in HeLa cells, where there are generally 10–30 per nucleus, paraspeckles are now known to also exist in all human primary cells, transformed cell lines, and tissue sections.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Their name is derived from their distribution in the nucleus; the "para" is short for parallel and the "speckles" refers to the splicing speckles to which they are always in close proximity.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Paraspeckles sequester nuclear proteins and RNA and thus appear to function as a molecular sponge that is involved in the regulation of gene expression.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Furthermore, paraspeckles are dynamic structures that are altered in response to changes in cellular metabolic activity.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] They are transcription dependent and in the absence of RNA Pol II transcription, the paraspeckle disappears and all of its associated protein components (PSP1, p54nrb, PSP2, CFI(m)68, and PSF) form a crescent shaped perinucleolar cap in the nucleolus.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] This phenomenon is demonstrated during the cell cycle.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] In the cell cycle, paraspeckles are present during interphase and during all of mitosis except for telophase.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] During telophase, when the two daughter nuclei are formed, there is no RNA Pol II transcription so the protein components instead form a perinucleolar cap.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Perichromatin fibrils are visible only under electron microscope.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] They are located next to the transcriptionally active chromatin and are hypothesized to be the sites of active pre-mRNA processing.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Clastosomes are small nuclear bodies (0.2–0.5 μm) described as having a thick ring-shape due to the peripheral capsule around these bodies.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] This name is derived from the Greek *klastos* (κλαστός), broken and *soma* (σῶμα), body.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Clastosomes are not typically present in normal cells, making them hard to detect.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] They form under high proteolytic conditions within the nucleus and degrade once there is a decrease in activity or if cells are treated with proteasome inhibitors.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The scarcity of clastosomes in cells indicates that they are not required for proteasome function.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Osmotic stress has also been shown to cause the formation of clastosomes.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] These nuclear bodies contain catalytic and regulatory subunits of the proteasome and its substrates, indicating that clastosomes are sites for degrading proteins.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The nucleus provides a site for genetic transcription that is segregated from the location of translation in the cytoplasm, allowing levels of gene regulation that are not available to prokaryotes.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The main function of the cell nucleus is to control gene expression and mediate the replication of DNA during the cell cycle.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The nuclear envelope allows control of the nuclear contents, and separates them from the rest of the cytoplasm where necessary.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] This regulatory mechanism occurs in the case of glycolysis, a cellular pathway for breaking down glucose to produce energy.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Hexokinase is an enzyme responsible for the first step of glycolysis, forming glucose-6-phosphate from glucose.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] At high concentrations of fructose-6-phosphate, a molecule made later from glucose-6-phosphate, a regulator protein removes hexokinase to the nucleus, where it forms a transcriptional repressor complex with nuclear proteins to reduce the expression of genes involved in glycolysis.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] In order to control which genes are being transcribed, the cell separates some transcription factor proteins responsible for regulating gene expression from physical access to the DNA until they are activated by other signaling pathways.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] This prevents even low levels of inappropriate gene expression.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] A nuclear localisation signal on the NF-κB protein allows it to be transported through the nuclear pore and into the nucleus, where it stimulates the transcription of the target genes.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The compartmentalization allows the cell to prevent translation of unspliced mRNA.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Eukaryotic mRNA contains introns that must be removed before being translated to produce functional proteins.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The splicing is done inside the nucleus before the mRNA can be accessed by ribosomes for translation.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Without the nucleus, ribosomes would translate newly transcribed (unprocessed) mRNA, resulting in malformed and nonfunctional proteins.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] It has been found that replication happens in a localised way in the cell nucleus.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] In the S phase of interphase of the cell cycle; replication takes place.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Contrary to the traditional view of moving replication forks along stagnant DNA, a concept of *replication factories* emerged, which means replication forks are concentrated towards some immobilised 'factory' regions through which the template DNA strands pass like conveyor belts.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Gene expression first involves transcription, in which DNA is used as a template to produce RNA.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] In the case of genes encoding proteins, that RNA produced from this process is messenger RNA (mRNA), which then needs to be translated by ribosomes to form a protein.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] As ribosomes are located outside the nucleus, mRNA produced needs to be exported.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Since the nucleus is the site of transcription, it also contains a variety of proteins that either directly mediate transcription or are involved in regulating the process.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Newly synthesized mRNA molecules are known as primary transcripts or pre-mRNA.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] They must undergo post-transcriptional modification in the nucleus before being exported to the cytoplasm; mRNA that appears in the cytoplasm without these modifications is degraded rather than used for protein translation.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The three main modifications are 5' capping, 3' polyadenylation, and RNA splicing.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] While in the nucleus, pre-mRNA is associated with a variety of proteins in complexes known as heterogeneous ribonucleoprotein particles (hnRNPs).
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Addition of the 5' cap occurs co-transcriptionally and is the first step in post-transcriptional modification.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The 3' poly-adenine tail is only added after transcription is complete.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] RNA splicing, carried out by a complex called the spliceosome, is the process by which introns, or regions of DNA that do not code for protein, are removed from the pre-mRNA and the remaining exons connected to re-form a single continuous molecule.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] This process normally occurs after 5' capping and 3' polyadenylation but can begin before synthesis is complete in transcripts with many exons.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Many pre-mRNAs can be spliced in multiple ways to produce different mature mRNAs that encode different protein sequences.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] This process is known as alternative splicing, and allows production of a large variety of proteins from a limited amount of DNA.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The entry and exit of large molecules from the nucleus is tightly controlled by the nuclear pore complexes.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Although small molecules can enter the nucleus without regulation, macromolecules such as RNA and proteins require association karyopherins called importins to enter the nucleus and exportins to exit.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] "Cargo" proteins that must be translocated from the cytoplasm to the nucleus contain short amino acid sequences known as nuclear localization signals, which are bound by importins, while those transported from the nucleus to the cytoplasm carry nuclear export signals bound by exportins.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The ability of importins and exportins to transport their cargo is regulated by GTPases, enzymes that hydrolyze the molecule guanosine triphosphate (GTP) to release energy.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The key GTPase in nuclear transport is Ran, which is bound to either GTP or GDP (guanosine diphosphate), depending on whether it is located in the nucleus or the cytoplasm.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Whereas importins depend on RanGTP to dissociate from their cargo, exportins require RanGTP in order to bind to their cargo.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Nuclear import depends on the importin binding its cargo in the cytoplasm and carrying it through the nuclear pore into the nucleus.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Inside the nucleus, RanGTP acts to separate the cargo from the importin, allowing the importin to exit the nucleus and be reused.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Nuclear export is similar, as the exportin binds the cargo inside the nucleus in a process facilitated by RanGTP, exits through the nuclear pore, and separates from its cargo in the cytoplasm.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Specialized export proteins exist for translocation of mature mRNA and tRNA to the cytoplasm after post-transcriptional modification is complete.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] This quality-control mechanism is important due to these molecules' central role in protein translation.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Mis-expression of a protein due to incomplete excision of exons or mis-incorporation of amino acids could have negative consequences for the cell; thus, incompletely modified RNA that reaches the cytoplasm is degraded rather than used in translation.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] During its lifetime, a nucleus may be broken down or destroyed, either in the process of cell division or as a consequence of apoptosis (the process of programmed cell death).
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] During these events, the structural components of the nucleus — the envelope and lamina — can be systematically degraded.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] In most cells, the disassembly of the nuclear envelope marks the end of the prophase of mitosis.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] However, this disassembly of the nucleus is not a universal feature of mitosis and does not occur in all cells.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Some unicellular eukaryotes (e.g., yeasts) undergo so-called closed mitosis, in which the nuclear envelope remains intact.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] In closed mitosis, the daughter chromosomes migrate to opposite poles of the nucleus, which then divides in two.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The cells of higher eukaryotes, however, usually undergo open mitosis, which is characterized by breakdown of the nuclear envelope.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The daughter chromosomes then migrate to opposite poles of the mitotic spindle, and new nuclei reassemble around them.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] At a certain point during the cell cycle in open mitosis, the cell divides to form two cells.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] In order for this process to be possible, each of the new daughter cells must have a full set of genes, a process requiring replication of the chromosomes as well as segregation of the separate sets.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] This occurs by the replicated chromosomes, the sister chromatids, attaching to microtubules, which in turn are attached to different centrosomes.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The sister chromatids can then be pulled to separate locations in the cell.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] In many cells, the centrosome is located in the cytoplasm, outside the nucleus; the microtubules would be unable to attach to the chromatids in the presence of the nuclear envelope.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Therefore, the early stages in the cell cycle, beginning in prophase and until around prometaphase, the nuclear membrane is dismantled.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Likewise, during the same period, the nuclear lamina is also disassembled, a process regulated by phosphorylation of the lamins by protein kinases such as the CDC2 protein kinase.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Towards the end of the cell cycle, the nuclear membrane is reformed, and around the same time, the nuclear lamina are reassembled by dephosphorylating the lamins.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] However, in dinoflagellates, the nuclear envelope remains intact, the centrosomes are located in the cytoplasm, and the microtubules come in contact with chromosomes, whose centromeric regions are incorporated into the nuclear envelope (the so-called closed mitosis with extranuclear spindle).
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] In many other protists (e.g., ciliates, sporozoans) and fungi, the centrosomes are intranuclear, and their nuclear envelope also does not disassemble during cell division.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Apoptosis is a controlled process in which the cell's structural components are destroyed, resulting in death of the cell.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Changes associated with apoptosis directly affect the nucleus and its contents, for example, in the condensation of chromatin and the disintegration of the nuclear envelope and lamina.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The destruction of the lamin networks is controlled by specialized apoptotic proteases called caspases, which cleave the lamin proteins and, thus, degrade the nucleus' structural integrity.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Lamin cleavage is sometimes used as a laboratory indicator of caspase activity in assays for early apoptotic activity.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Cells that express mutant caspase-resistant lamins are deficient in nuclear changes related to apoptosis, suggesting that lamins play a role in initiating the events that lead to apoptotic degradation of the nucleus.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Inhibition of lamin assembly itself is an inducer of apoptosis.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The nuclear envelope acts as a barrier that prevents both DNA and RNA viruses from entering the nucleus.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Some viruses require access to proteins inside the nucleus in order to replicate and/or assemble.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] DNA viruses, such as herpesvirus replicate and assemble in the cell nucleus, and exit by budding through the inner nuclear membrane.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] This process is accompanied by disassembly of the lamina on the nuclear face of the inner membrane.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Initially, it has been suspected that immunoglobulins in general and autoantibodies in particular do not enter the nucleus.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Now there is a body of evidence that under pathological conditions (e.g. lupus erythematosus) IgG can enter the nucleus.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Most eukaryotic cell types usually have a single nucleus, but some have no nuclei, while others have several.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] This can result from normal development, as in the maturation of mammalian red blood cells, or from faulty cell division.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] An anucleated cell contains no nucleus and is, therefore, incapable of dividing to produce daughter cells.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The best-known anucleated cell is the mammalian red blood cell, or erythrocyte, which also lacks other organelles such as mitochondria, and serves primarily as a transport vessel to ferry oxygen from the lungs to the body's tissues.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Erythrocytes mature through erythropoiesis in the bone marrow, where they lose their nuclei, organelles, and ribosomes.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The nucleus is expelled during the process of differentiation from an erythroblast to a reticulocyte, which is the immediate precursor of the mature erythrocyte.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The presence of mutagens may induce the release of some immature "micronucleated" erythrocytes into the bloodstream.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Anucleated cells can also arise from flawed cell division in which one daughter lacks a nucleus and the other has two nuclei.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] In flowering plants, this condition occurs in sieve tube elements.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Multinucleated cells contain multiple nuclei.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Most acantharean species of protozoa and some fungi in mycorrhizae have naturally multinucleated cells.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Other examples include the intestinal parasites in the genus *Giardia*, which have two nuclei per cell.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Ciliates have two kinds of nuclei in a single cell, a somatic macronucleus and a germline micronucleus.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] In humans, skeletal muscle cells, also called myocytes and syncytium, become multinucleated during development; the resulting arrangement of nuclei near the periphery of the cells allows maximal intracellular space for myofibrils.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Other multinucleate cells in the human are osteoclasts a type of bone cell.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Multinucleated and binucleated cells can also be abnormal in humans; for example, cells arising from the fusion of monocytes and macrophages, known as giant multinucleated cells, sometimes accompany inflammation and are also implicated in tumor formation.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] A number of dinoflagellates are known to have two nuclei.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Unlike other multinucleated cells these nuclei contain two distinct lineages of DNA: one from the dinoflagellate and the other from a symbiotic diatom.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] As the major defining characteristic of the eukaryotic cell, the nucleus's evolutionary origin has been the subject of much speculation.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Four major hypotheses have been proposed to explain the existence of the nucleus, although none have yet earned widespread support.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The first model known as the "syntrophic model" proposes that a symbiotic relationship between the archaea and bacteria created the nucleus-containing eukaryotic cell.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] (Organisms of the Archaeal and Bacterial domains have no cell nucleus.) It is hypothesized that the symbiosis originated when ancient archaea similar to modern methanogenic archaea, invaded and lived within bacteria similar to modern myxobacteria, eventually forming the early nucleus.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] This theory is analogous to the accepted theory for the origin of eukaryotic mitochondria and chloroplasts, which are thought to have developed from a similar endosymbiotic relationship between proto-eukaryotes and aerobic bacteria.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] One possibility is that the nuclear membrane arose as a new membrane system following the origin of mitochondria in an archaebacterial host.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The nuclear membrane may have served to protect the genome from damaging reactive oxygen species produced by the protomitochondria.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The archaeal origin of the nucleus is supported by observations that archaea and eukarya have similar genes for certain proteins, including histones.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Observations that myxobacteria are motile, can form multicellular complexes, and possess kinases and G proteins similar to eukarya, support a bacterial origin for the eukaryotic cell.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] A second model proposes that proto-eukaryotic cells evolved from bacteria without an endosymbiotic stage.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] This model is based on the existence of modern Planctomycetota bacteria that possess a nuclear structure with primitive pores and other compartmentalized membrane structures.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] A similar proposal states that a eukaryote-like cell, the hypothetical *chronocyte*, evolved first and phagocytosed archaea and bacteria to generate the nucleus and the eukaryotic cell.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The most controversial model, known as *viral eukaryogenesis*, posits that the membrane-bound nucleus, along with other eukaryotic features, originated from the infection of a prokaryote by a virus.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The suggestion is based on similarities between eukaryotes and viruses such as linear DNA strands, mRNA capping, and tight binding to proteins (analogizing histones to viral envelopes).
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] One version of the proposal suggests that the nucleus evolved in concert with phagocytosis to form an early cellular "predator".
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Another variant proposes that eukaryotes originated from early archaea infected by poxviruses, on the basis of observed similarity between the DNA polymerases in modern poxviruses and eukaryotes.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] It has been suggested that the unresolved question of the evolution of sex could be related to the viral eukaryogenesis hypothesis.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The nucleus was the first organelle to be discovered.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] What is most likely the oldest preserved drawing dates back to the early microscopist Antonie van Leeuwenhoek (1632–1723).
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] He observed a "lumen", the nucleus, in the red blood cells of salmon.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Unlike mammalian red blood cells, those of other vertebrates still contain nuclei.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The nucleus was also described by Franz Bauer in 1804 and in more detail in 1831 by Scottish botanist Robert Brown in a talk at the Linnean Society of London.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Brown was studying orchids under the microscope when he observed an opaque area, which he called the "areola" or "nucleus", in the cells of the flower's outer layer.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] He did not suggest a potential function.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] In 1838, Matthias Schleiden proposed that the nucleus plays a role in generating cells, thus he introduced the name "**cytoblast**" ("cell builder").
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] He believed that he had observed new cells assembling around "cytoblasts".
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Franz Meyen was a strong opponent of this view, having already described cells multiplying by division and believing that many cells would have no nuclei.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The idea that cells can be generated de novo, by the "cytoblast" or otherwise, contradicted work by Robert Remak (1852) and Rudolf Virchow (1855) who decisively propagated the new paradigm that cells are generated solely by cells ("*Omnis cellula e cellula*").
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The function of the nucleus remained unclear.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Between 1877 and 1878, Oscar Hertwig published several studies on the fertilization of sea urchin eggs, showing that the nucleus of the sperm enters the oocyte and fuses with its nucleus.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] This was the first time it was suggested that an individual develops from a (single) nucleated cell.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] This was in contradiction to Ernst Haeckel's theory that the complete phylogeny of a species would be repeated during embryonic development, including generation of the first nucleated cell from a "monerula", a structureless mass of primordial protoplasm ("Urschleim").
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Therefore, the necessity of the sperm nucleus for fertilization was discussed for quite some time.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] However, Hertwig confirmed his observation in other animal groups, including amphibians and molluscs.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] Eduard Strasburger produced the same results for plants in 1884.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] This paved the way to assign the nucleus an important role in heredity.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] In 1873, August Weismann postulated the equivalence of the maternal and paternal germ *cells* for heredity.
[src:cell-biology/cell-nucleus] The function of the nucleus as carrier of genetic information became clear only later, after mitosis was discovered and the Mendelian rules were rediscovered at the beginning of the 20th century; the chromosome theory of heredity was therefore developed.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] The **cytoskeleton** is a complex, dynamic network of interlinking protein filaments present in the cytoplasm of all cells, including those of bacteria and archaea.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] In eukaryotes, it extends from the cell nucleus to the cell membrane and is composed of similar proteins in the various organisms.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] It is composed of three main components: microfilaments, intermediate filaments, and microtubules, and these are all capable of rapid growth and/or disassembly depending on the cell's requirements.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] The cytoskeleton can perform many functions.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Its primary function is to give the cell its shape and mechanical resistance to deformation, and through association with extracellular connective tissue and other cells it stabilizes entire tissues.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] The cytoskeleton can also contract, thereby deforming the cell and the cell's environment and allowing cells to migrate.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Furthermore, it can form specialized structures, such as flagella, cilia, lamellipodia and podosomes.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] The structure, function and dynamic behavior of the cytoskeleton can be very different, depending on organism and cell type.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Even within one cell, the cytoskeleton can change through association with other proteins and the previous history of the network.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] A large-scale example of an action performed by the cytoskeleton is muscle contraction.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] This is carried out by groups of highly specialized cells working together.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] A main component in the cytoskeleton that helps show the true function of this muscle contraction is the microfilament.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Microfilaments are composed of the most abundant cellular protein known as actin.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] During contraction of a muscle, within each muscle cell, myosin molecular motors collectively exert forces on parallel actin filaments.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Muscle contraction starts from nerve impulses which then causes increased amounts of calcium to be released from the sarcoplasmic reticulum.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Increases in calcium in the cytosol allows muscle contraction to begin with the help of two proteins, tropomyosin and troponin.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Tropomyosin inhibits the interaction between actin and myosin, while troponin senses the increase in calcium and releases the inhibition.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] This action contracts the muscle cell, and through the synchronous process in many muscle cells, the entire muscle.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Koltsov proposed that the shape of cells was determined by a network of tubules that he termed the cytoskeleton.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] The concept of a protein mosaic that dynamically coordinated cytoplasmic biochemistry was proposed by Rudolph Peters in 1929 while the term (*cytosquelette*, in French) was first introduced by French embryologist Paul Wintrebert in 1931.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] When the cytoskeleton was first introduced, it was thought to be an uninteresting gel-like substance that helped organelles stay in place.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Much research took place to try to understand the purpose of the cytoskeleton and its components.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Initially, it was thought that the cytoskeleton was exclusive to eukaryotes but in 1992 it was discovered to be present in prokaryotes as well.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] This discovery came after the realization that bacteria possess proteins that are homologous to tubulin and actin; the main components of the eukaryotic cytoskeleton.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Eukaryotic cells contain three main kinds of cytoskeletal filaments: microfilaments, microtubules, and intermediate filaments.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] In neurons the intermediate filaments are known as neurofilaments.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Each type is formed by the polymerization of a distinct type of protein subunit and has its own characteristic shape and intracellular distribution.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Microfilaments are polymers of the protein actin and are 7 nm in diameter.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Microtubules are composed of tubulin and are 25 nm in diameter.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Intermediate filaments are composed of various proteins, depending on the type of cell in which they are found; they are normally 8-12 nm in diameter.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] The cytoskeleton provides the cell with structure and shape, and by excluding macromolecules from some of the cytosol, it adds to the level of macromolecular crowding in this compartment.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Cytoskeletal elements interact extensively and intimately with cellular membranes.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Research into neurodegenerative disorders such as Parkinson's disease, Alzheimer's disease, Huntington's disease, and amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS) indicate that the cytoskeleton is affected in these diseases.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Parkinson's disease is marked by the degradation of neurons, resulting in tremors, rigidity, and other non-motor symptoms.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Research has shown that microtubule assembly and stability in the cytoskeleton is compromised causing the neurons to degrade over time.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] In Alzheimer's disease, tau proteins which stabilize microtubules malfunction in the progression of the illness causing pathology of the cytoskeleton.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Excess glutamine in the Huntington protein (huntingtin) involved with linking vesicles onto the cytoskeleton is also proposed to be a factor in the development of Huntington's Disease.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis results in a loss of movement caused by the degradation of motor neurons, and also involves defects of the cytoskeleton.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Stuart Hameroff and Roger Penrose suggest a role of microtubule vibrations in neurons in the origin of consciousness.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Accessory proteins including motor proteins regulate and link the filaments to other cell compounds and each other and are essential for controlled assembly of cytoskeletal filaments in particular locations.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] A number of small-molecule cytoskeletal drugs have been discovered that interact with actin and microtubules.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] These compounds have proven useful in studying the cytoskeleton, and several have clinical applications.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Microfilaments, also known as actin filaments, are composed of linear polymers of G-actin proteins, and generate force when the growing (plus) end of the filament pushes against a barrier, such as the cell membrane.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] They also act as tracks for the movement of myosin molecules that affix to the microfilament and "walk" along them.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] In general, the major component or protein of microfilaments are actin.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] The G-actin monomer combines to form a polymer which continues to form the microfilament (actin filament).
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] These subunits then assemble into two chains that intertwine into what are called F-actin chains.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Myosin motoring along F-actin filaments generates contractile forces in so-called actomyosin fibers, both in muscle as well as most non-muscle cell types.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Actin structures are controlled by the Rho family of small GTP-binding proteins such as Rho itself for contractile acto-myosin filaments ("stress fibers"), Rac for lamellipodia and Cdc42 for filopodia.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Intermediate filaments are a part of the cytoskeleton of many eukaryotic cells.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] These filaments, averaging 10 nanometers in diameter, are more stable (strongly bound) than microfilaments, and heterogeneous constituents of the cytoskeleton.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Like actin filaments, they function in the maintenance of cell-shape by bearing tension (microtubules, by contrast, resist compression but can also bear tension during mitosis and during the positioning of the centrosome).
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Intermediate filaments organize the internal tridimensional structure of the cell, anchoring organelles and serving as structural components of the nuclear lamina.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] They also participate in some cell-cell and cell-matrix junctions.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Nuclear lamina exist in all animals and all tissues.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Some animals like the fruit fly do not have any cytoplasmic intermediate filaments.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] In those animals that express cytoplasmic intermediate filaments, these are tissue specific.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Keratin intermediate filaments in epithelial cells provide protection for different mechanical stresses the skin may endure.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] They also provide protection for organs against metabolic, oxidative, and chemical stresses.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Strengthening of epithelial cells with these intermediate filaments may prevent onset of apoptosis, or cell death, by reducing the probability of stress.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Intermediate filaments are most commonly known as the support system or "scaffolding" for the cell and nucleus while also playing a role in some cell functions.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] In combination with proteins and desmosomes, the intermediate filaments form cell-cell connections and anchor the cell-matrix junctions that are used in messaging between cells as well as vital functions of the cell.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] These connections allow the cell to communicate through the desmosome of multiple cells to adjust structures of the tissue based on signals from the cells environment.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Mutations in the IF proteins have been shown to cause serious medical issues such as premature aging, desmin mutations compromising organs, Alexander Disease, and muscular dystrophy.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Microtubules are hollow cylinders about 23 nm in diameter (lumen diameter of approximately 15 nm), most commonly comprising 13 protofilaments that, in turn, are polymers of alpha and beta tubulin.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] They have a very dynamic behavior, binding GTP for polymerization.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] They are commonly organized by the centrosome.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] In nine triplet sets (star-shaped), they form the centrioles, and in nine doublets oriented about two additional microtubules (wheel-shaped), they form cilia and flagella.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] The latter formation is commonly referred to as a "9+2" arrangement, wherein each doublet is connected to another by the protein dynein.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] As both flagella and cilia are structural components of the cell, and are maintained by microtubules, they can be considered part of the cytoskeleton.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] There are two types of cilia: motile and non-motile cilia.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Cilia are short and more numerous than flagella.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] The motile cilia have a rhythmic waving or beating motion compared to the non-motile cilia which receive sensory information for the cell; processing signals from the other cells or the fluids surrounding it.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Additionally, the microtubules control the beating (movement) of the cilia and flagella.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Also, the dynein arms attached to the microtubules function as the molecular motors.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] The motion of the cilia and flagella is created by the microtubules sliding past one another, which requires ATP.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] In addition to the roles described above, Stuart Hameroff and Roger Penrose have proposed that microtubules function in consciousness.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Septins are a group of the highly conserved GTP binding proteins found in eukaryotes.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Different septins form protein complexes with each other.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] These can assemble to filaments and rings.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Therefore, septins can be considered part of the cytoskeleton.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] The function of septins in cells include serving as a localized attachment site for other proteins, and preventing the diffusion of certain molecules from one cell compartment to another.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] In yeast cells, they build scaffolding to provide structural support during cell division and compartmentalize parts of the cell.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Recent research in human cells suggests that septins build cages around bacterial pathogens, immobilizing the harmful microbes and preventing them from invading other cells.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Spectrin is a cytoskeletal protein that lines the intracellular side of the plasma membrane in many eukaryotic cells particularly animal cells, but is not present in plant cells, or yeast.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Spectrin forms pentagonal or hexagonal arrangements, forming a scaffolding and playing an important role in maintenance of plasma membrane integrity and cytoskeletal structure.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] In budding yeast (an important model organism), actin forms cortical patches, actin cables, and a cytokinetic ring and the cap.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Cortical patches are discrete actin bodies on the membrane and are vital for endocytosis, especially the recycling of glucan synthase which is important for cell wall synthesis.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Actin cables are bundles of actin filaments and are involved in the transport of vesicles towards the cap (which contains a number of different proteins to polarize cell growth) and in the positioning of mitochondria.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] The cytokinetic ring forms and constricts around the site of cell division.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Prior to the work of Jones et al., 2001, the cell wall was believed to be the deciding factor for many bacterial cell shapes, including rods and spirals.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] When studied, many misshapen bacteria were found to have mutations linked to development of a cell envelope.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] The cytoskeleton was once thought to be a feature only of eukaryotic cells, but homologues to all the major proteins of the eukaryotic cytoskeleton have been found in prokaryotes.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Harold Erickson notes that before 1992, only eukaryotes were believed to have cytoskeleton components.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] However, research in the early '90s suggested that bacteria and archaea had homologues of actin and tubulin, and that these were the basis of eukaryotic microtubules and microfilaments.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Three laboratories independently discovered that FtsZ, a protein already known as a key player in bacterial cytokinesis, had the "tubulin signature sequence" present in all α-, β-, and γ-tubulins.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] However, some structures in the bacterial cytoskeleton may not have been identified as of yet.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] FtsZ was the first protein of the prokaryotic cytoskeleton to be identified.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Like tubulin, FtsZ forms filaments in the presence of guanosine triphosphate (GTP), but these filaments do not group into tubules.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] During cell division, FtsZ is the first protein to move to the division site, and is essential for recruiting other proteins that synthesize the new cell wall between the dividing cells.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Prokaryotic actin-like proteins, such as MreB, are involved in the maintenance of cell shape.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] All non-spherical bacteria have genes encoding actin-like proteins, and these proteins form a helical network beneath the cell membrane that guides the proteins involved in cell wall biosynthesis.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Some plasmids encode a separate system that involves an actin-like protein ParM.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Filaments of ParM exhibit dynamic instability, and may partition plasmid DNA into the dividing daughter cells by a mechanism analogous to that used by microtubules during eukaryotic mitosis.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] The bacterium *Caulobacter crescentus* contains a third protein, crescentin, that is related to the intermediate filaments of eukaryotic cells.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Crescentin is also involved in maintaining cell shape, such as helical and vibrioid forms of bacteria, but the mechanism by which it does this is currently unclear.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Additionally, curvature could be described by the displacement of crescentic filaments, after the disruption of peptidoglycan synthesis.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] The cytoskeleton is a highly anisotropic and dynamic network, constantly remodeling itself in response to the changing cellular microenvironment.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] The network influences cell mechanics and dynamics by differentially polymerizing and depolymerizing its constituent filaments (primarily actin and myosin, but microtubules and intermediate filaments also play a role).
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] This generates forces, which play an important role in informing the cell of its microenvironment.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Specifically, forces such as tension, stiffness, and shear forces have all been shown to influence cell fate, differentiation, migration, and motility.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Through a process called "mechanotransduction," the cell remodels its cytoskeleton to sense and respond to these forces.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Mechanotransduction relies heavily on focal adhesions, which essentially connect the intracellular cytoskeleton with the extracellular matrix (ECM).
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Through focal adhesions, the cell is able to integrate extracellular forces into intracellular ones as the proteins present at focal adhesions undergo conformational changes to initiate signaling cascades.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Proteins such as focal adhesion kinase (FAK) and Src have been shown to transduce force signals in response to cellular activities such as proliferation and differentiation, and are hypothesized to be key sensors in the mechanotransduction pathway.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] As a result of mechanotransduction, the cytoskeleton changes its composition and/or orientation to accommodate the force stimulus and ensure the cell responds accordingly.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] The cytoskeleton changes the mechanics of the cell in response to detected forces.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] For example, increasing tension within the plasma membrane makes it more likely that ion channels will open, which increases ion conductance and makes cellular change ion influx or efflux much more likely.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Moreover, the mechanical properties of cells determine how far and where, directionally, a force will propagate throughout the cell and how it will change cell dynamics.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] A membrane protein that is not closely coupled to the cytoskeleton, for instance, will not produce a significant effect on the cortical actin network if it is subjected to a specifically directed force.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] However, membrane proteins that are more closely associated with the cytoskeleton will induce a more significant response.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] In this way, the anisotropy of the cytoskeleton serves to more keenly direct cell responses to intra or extracellular signals.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] The specific pathways and mechanisms by which the cytoskeleton senses and responds to forces are still under investigation.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] However, the long-range order generated by the cytoskeleton is known to contribute to mechanotransduction.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Cells, which are around 10–50 μm in diameter, are several thousand times larger than the molecules found within the cytoplasm that are essential to coordinate cellular activities.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Because cells are so large in comparison to essential biomolecules, it is difficult, in the absence of an organizing network, for different parts of the cytoplasm to communicate.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Moreover, biomolecules must polymerize to lengths comparable to the length of the cell, but resulting polymers can be highly disorganized and unable to effectively transmit signals from one part of the cytoplasm to another.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Thus, it is necessary to have the cytoskeleton to organize the polymers and ensure that they can effectively communicate across the entirety of the cell.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] By definition, the cytoskeleton is composed of proteins that can form longitudinal arrays (fibres) in all organisms.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] These filament forming proteins have been classified into 4 classes.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Tubulin-like, actin-like, Walker A cytoskeletal ATPases (WACA-proteins), and intermediate filaments.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Tubulin-like proteins are tubulin in eukaryotes and FtsZ, TubZ, RepX in prokaryotes.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Actin-like proteins are actin in eukaryotes and MreB, FtsA in prokaryotes.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] An example of a WACA-proteins, which are mostly found in prokaryotes, is MinD.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Examples for intermediate filaments, which have almost exclusively been found in animals (i.e. eukaryotes) are the lamins, keratins, vimentin, neurofilaments, and desmin.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Although tubulin-like proteins share some amino acid sequence similarity, their equivalence in protein-fold and the similarity in the GTP binding site is more striking.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] The same holds true for the actin-like proteins and their structure and ATP binding domain.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Cytoskeletal proteins are usually correlated with cell shape, DNA segregation and cell division in prokaryotes and eukaryotes.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Which proteins fulfill which task is very different.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] For example, DNA segregation in all eukaryotes happens through use of tubulin, but in prokaryotes either WACA proteins, actin-like or tubulin-like proteins can be used.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Cell division is mediated in eukaryotes by actin, but in prokaryotes usually by tubulin-like (often FtsZ-ring) proteins and sometimes (Thermoproteota) ESCRT-III, which in eukaryotes still has a role in the last step of division.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Cytoplasmic streaming, also known as cyclosis, is the active movement of a cell's contents along the components of the cytoskeleton.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] While mainly seen in plants, all cell types use this process for transportation of waste, nutrients, and organelles to other parts of the cell.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Plant and algae cells are generally larger than many other cells; so cytoplasmic streaming is important in these types of cells.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] This is because the cell's extra volume requires cytoplasmic streaming in order to move organelles throughout the entire cell.
[src:cell-biology/cytoskeleton] Organelles move along microfilaments in the cytoskeleton driven by myosin motors binding and pushing along actin filament bundles.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The **endoplasmic reticulum** (**ER**) is a part of a transportation system of the eukaryotic cell, and has many other important functions such as protein folding.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The word endoplasmic means "within the cytoplasm", and reticulum is Latin for "little net".
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] It is a type of organelle made up of two subunits – **rough endoplasmic reticulum** (**RER**), and **smooth endoplasmic reticulum** (**SER**).
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The endoplasmic reticulum is found in most eukaryotic cells and forms an interconnected network of flattened, membrane-enclosed sacs known as cisternae in the RER, and tubular structures in the SER.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The membranes of the ER are continuous with the outer nuclear membrane.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The endoplasmic reticulum is not found in red blood cells, or spermatozoa.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] There are two types of ER that share many of the same proteins and engage in certain common activities such as the synthesis of certain lipids and cholesterol.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] Different types of cells contain different ratios of the two types of ER depending on the activities of the cell.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] RER is found mainly toward the nucleus of the cell and SER towards the cell membrane or plasma membrane of the cell.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The outer (cytosolic) face of the RER is studded with ribosomes that are the sites of protein synthesis.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The RER is especially prominent in cells such as hepatocytes.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The SER lacks ribosomes and functions in lipid synthesis but not metabolism, the production of steroid hormones, and detoxification.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The SER is especially abundant in mammalian liver and gonad cells.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The ER was observed by light microscopy by Charles Garnier in 1897, who coined the term *ergastoplasm*.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The lacy membranes of the endoplasmic reticulum were first seen by electron microscopy in 1945 by Keith R.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The general structure of the endoplasmic reticulum is a network of membranes called cisternae.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] These sac-like structures are held together by the cytoskeleton.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The phospholipid membrane encloses the cisternal space (or lumen), which is continuous with the perinuclear space but separate from the cytosol.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The functions of the endoplasmic reticulum can be summarized as the synthesis and export of proteins and membrane lipids, but varies between ER and cell type and cell function.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The quantity of both rough and smooth endoplasmic reticulum in a cell can slowly interchange from one type to the other, depending on the changing metabolic activities of the cell.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] Transformation can include embedding of new proteins in membrane as well as structural changes.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] Changes in protein content may occur without noticeable structural changes.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The surface of the rough endoplasmic reticulum (often abbreviated *RER* or *rough ER*; also called *granular endoplasmic reticulum*) is studded with protein-manufacturing ribosomes giving it a "rough" appearance (hence its name).
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The binding site of the ribosome on the rough endoplasmic reticulum is the translocon.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] However, the ribosomes are not a stable part of this organelle's structure as they are constantly being bound and released from the membrane.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] A ribosome only binds to the RER once a specific protein-nucleic acid complex forms in the cytosol.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] This special complex forms when a free ribosome begins translating the mRNA of a protein destined for the secretory pathway.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The first 5–30 amino acids polymerized encode a signal peptide, a molecular message that is recognized and bound by a signal recognition particle (SRP).
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] Translation pauses and the ribosome complex binds to the RER translocon where translation continues with the nascent (new) protein forming into the RER lumen and/or membrane.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The protein is processed in the ER lumen by an enzyme (a signal peptidase), which removes the signal peptide.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] Ribosomes at this point may be released back into the cytosol; however, non-translating ribosomes are also known to stay associated with translocons.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The membrane of the rough endoplasmic reticulum is in the form of large double-membrane sheets that are located near, and continuous with, the outer layer of the nuclear envelope.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The double membrane sheets are stacked and connected through several right- or left-handed helical ramps, the "Terasaki ramps", giving rise to a structure resembling a parking garage.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] Although there is no continuous membrane between the endoplasmic reticulum and the Golgi apparatus, membrane-bound transport vesicles shuttle proteins between these two compartments.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] Vesicles are surrounded by coating proteins called COPI and COPII.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] COPII targets vesicles to the Golgi apparatus and COPI marks them to be brought back to the rough endoplasmic reticulum.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The rough endoplasmic reticulum works in concert with the Golgi complex to target new proteins to their proper destinations.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The second method of transport out of the endoplasmic reticulum involves areas called membrane contact sites, where the membranes of the endoplasmic reticulum and other organelles are held closely together, allowing the transfer of lipids and other small molecules.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The RER has ribosomes while the SER does not.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] In most cells the smooth endoplasmic reticulum (abbreviated **SER**) is scarce.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] Instead there are areas where the ER is partly smooth and partly rough: the transitional ER.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The transitional ER gets its name because it contains ER exit sites, areas where the transport vesicles, which contain lipids and proteins made in the ER, detach from the ER and start moving to the Golgi apparatus.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] Specialized cells can have a lot of smooth endoplasmic reticulum and in these cells the smooth ER has many functions.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] It synthesizes lipids, phospholipids, and steroids.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] Cells which secrete these products, such as those in the testes, ovaries, and sebaceous glands have an abundance of smooth endoplasmic reticulum.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] It also carries out the metabolism of carbohydrates, detoxification of natural metabolism products and of alcohol and drugs, attachment of receptors on cell membrane proteins, and steroid metabolism.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] In muscle cells, it regulates calcium ion concentration.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] Smooth endoplasmic reticulum is found in a variety of cell types (both animal and plant), and it serves different functions in each.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The smooth endoplasmic reticulum also contains the enzyme glucose-6-phosphatase, which converts glucose-6-phosphate to glucose, a step in gluconeogenesis.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] It is connected to the nuclear envelope and consists of tubules that are located near the cell periphery.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] These tubes sometimes branch forming a network that is reticular in appearance.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] In some cells, there are dilated areas like the sacs of rough endoplasmic reticulum.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The network of smooth endoplasmic reticulum allows for an increased surface area to be devoted to the action or storage of key enzymes and the products of these enzymes.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The sarcoplasmic reticulum (SR), from the Greek σάρξ *sarx* ("flesh"), is smooth ER found in muscle cells.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The only structural difference between this organelle and the smooth endoplasmic reticulum is the composition of proteins they have, both bound to their membranes and drifting within the confines of their lumens.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] This fundamental difference is indicative of their functions: The endoplasmic reticulum synthesizes molecules, while the sarcoplasmic reticulum stores calcium ions and pumps them out into the sarcoplasm when the muscle fiber is stimulated.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] After their release from the sarcoplasmic reticulum, calcium ions interact with contractile proteins that utilize ATP to shorten the muscle fiber.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The sarcoplasmic reticulum plays a major role in excitation-contraction coupling.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The endoplasmic reticulum serves many general functions, including the folding of protein molecules in sacs called cisternae and the transport of synthesized proteins in vesicles to the Golgi apparatus.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] Rough endoplasmic reticulum is also involved in protein synthesis.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] Correct folding of newly made proteins is made possible by several endoplasmic reticulum chaperone proteins, including protein disulfide isomerase (PDI), ERp29, the Hsp70 family member BiP/Grp78, calnexin, calreticulin, and the peptidylprolyl isomerase family.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] Only properly folded proteins are transported from the rough ER to the Golgi apparatus – unfolded proteins cause an unfolded protein response as a stress response in the ER.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] Disturbances in redox regulation, calcium regulation, glucose deprivation, and viral infection or the over-expression of proteins can lead to endoplasmic reticulum stress response (ER stress), a state in which the folding of proteins slows, leading to an increase in unfolded proteins.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] This stress is emerging as a potential cause of damage in hypoxia/ischemia, insulin resistance, and other disorders.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] Secretory proteins, mostly glycoproteins, are moved across the endoplasmic reticulum membrane.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] Proteins that are transported by the endoplasmic reticulum throughout the cell are marked with an address tag called a signal sequence.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The N-terminus (one end) of a polypeptide chain (i.e., a protein) contains a few amino acids that work as an address tag, which are removed when the polypeptide reaches its destination.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] Nascent peptides reach the ER via the translocon, a membrane-embedded multiprotein complex.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] Proteins that are destined for places outside the endoplasmic reticulum are packed into transport vesicles and moved along the cytoskeleton toward their destination.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] In human fibroblasts, the ER is always co-distributed with microtubules and the depolymerisation of the latter cause its co-aggregation with mitochondria, which are also associated with the ER.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The endoplasmic reticulum is also part of a protein sorting pathway.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] It is, in essence, the transportation system of the eukaryotic cell.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The majority of its resident proteins are retained within it through a retention motif.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] This motif is composed of four amino acids at the end of the protein sequence.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The most common retention sequences are KDEL for lumen-located proteins and KKXX for transmembrane proteins.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] However, variations of KDEL and KKXX do occur, and other sequences can also give rise to endoplasmic reticulum retention.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] It is not known whether such variation can lead to sub-ER localizations.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] There are three KDEL (1, 2 and 3) receptors in mammalian cells, and they have a very high degree of sequence identity.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The functional differences between these receptors remain to be established.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The endoplasmic reticulum does not harbor an ATP-regeneration machinery, and therefore requires ATP import from mitochondria.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The imported ATP is vital for the ER to carry out its house keeping cellular functions, such as for protein folding and trafficking.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The ER ATP transporter, SLC35B1/AXER, was recently cloned and characterized, and the mitochondria supply ATP to the ER through a *Ca2+-antagonized transport into the ER* (*CaATiER*) mechanism.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The *CaATiER* mechanism shows sensitivity to cytosolic Ca2+ ranging from high nM to low μM range, with the Ca2+-sensing element yet to be identified and validated.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] Beyond its biosynthetic and homeostatic roles, the endoplasmic reticulum is highly dynamic and forms membrane contact sites with other organelles and the plasma membrane, supporting lipid exchange, Ca2+ signalling and spatial control of signalling pathways.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] In migrating cells, ER–plasma membrane contact sites can become polarized, forming rear-to-front gradients that help maintain front–back polarity and directional migration.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] In epithelial monolayers, ER architecture can be reorganized by tissue edge curvature, influencing epithelial migration modes and tissue remodelling dynamics.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] Increased and supraphysiological ER stress in pancreatic β cells disrupts normal insulin secretion, leading to hyperinsulinemia and consequently peripheral insulin resistance associated with obesity in humans.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] Human clinical trials also suggested a causal link between obesity-induced increase in insulin secretion and peripheral insulin resistance.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] Abnormalities in XBP1 lead to a heightened endoplasmic reticulum stress response and subsequently causes a higher susceptibility for inflammatory processes that may even contribute to Alzheimer's disease.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] In the colon, XBP1 anomalies have been linked to the inflammatory bowel diseases including Crohn's disease.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The unfolded protein response (UPR) is a cellular stress response related to the endoplasmic reticulum.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The UPR is activated in response to an accumulation of unfolded or misfolded proteins in the lumen of the endoplasmic reticulum.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] The UPR functions to restore normal function of the cell by halting protein translation, degrading misfolded proteins, and activating the signaling pathways that lead to increasing the production of molecular chaperones involved in protein folding.
[src:cell-biology/endoplasmic-reticulum] Sustained overactivation of the UPR has been implicated in prion diseases as well as several other neurodegenerative diseases and the inhibition of the UPR could become a treatment for those diseases.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] **mitochondria**) is an organelle found in the cells of most eukaryotes, such as animals, plants and fungi.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Mitochondria have a double membrane structure and use aerobic respiration to generate adenosine triphosphate (ATP), which is used throughout the cell as a source of chemical energy.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] They were discovered by Albert von Kölliker in 1857 in the voluntary muscles of insects.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The term *mitochondrion*, meaning "a thread-like granule", was coined by Carl Benda in 1898.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The mitochondrion is popularly nicknamed the "powerhouse of the cell", a phrase popularized by Philip Siekevitz in a 1957 *Scientific American* article of the same name.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Mitochondria are commonly between 0.75 and 3 μm2 in cross section, but vary considerably in size and structure.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Unless specifically stained, they are not visible.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The mitochondrion is composed of compartments that carry out specialized functions.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] These compartments or regions include the outer membrane, intermembrane space, inner membrane, cristae, and matrix.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] In addition to supplying cellular energy, mitochondria are involved in other tasks, such as signaling, cellular differentiation, and cell death, as well as maintaining control of the cell cycle and cell growth.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Mitochondrial biogenesis is in turn temporally coordinated with these cellular processes.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Mitochondria are implicated in human disorders and conditions such as mitochondrial diseases, cardiac dysfunction, heart failure, and autism.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The number of mitochondria in a cell varies widely by organism, tissue, and cell type.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] A mature red blood cell has no mitochondria, whereas a liver cell can have more than 2000.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Although most of a eukaryotic cell's DNA is contained in the cell nucleus, the mitochondrion has its own genome ("mitogenome") that is similar to bacterial genomes.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Mitochondria may have a number of different shapes.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] A mitochondrion contains outer and inner membranes composed of phospholipid bilayers and proteins.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The two membranes have different properties.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The matrix (space within the inner membrane), which is a fluid.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The inner membrane of mitochondria have folding to increase surface area, which in turn increases ATP (adenosine triphosphate) production.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Mitochondria stripped of their outer membrane are called mitoplasts.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The **outer mitochondrial membrane**, which encloses the entire organelle, is 60 to 75 angstroms (Å) thick.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] It has a protein-to-phospholipid ratio similar to that of the cell membrane (about 1:1 by weight).
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] It contains large numbers of integral membrane proteins called porins.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] A major trafficking protein is the pore-forming voltage-dependent anion channel (VDAC).
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The VDAC is the primary transporter of nucleotides, ions and metabolites between the cytosol and the intermembrane space.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] It is formed as a beta barrel that spans the outer membrane, similar to that in the gram-negative bacterial outer membrane.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Larger proteins can enter the mitochondrion if a signaling sequence at their N-terminus binds to a large multisubunit protein called translocase in the outer membrane, which then actively moves them across the membrane.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Mitochondrial pro-proteins are imported through specialised translocation complexes.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The outer membrane also contains enzymes involved in activities such as the elongation of fatty acids, oxidation of epinephrine, and the degradation of tryptophan.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] These enzymes include monoamine oxidase, rotenone-insensitive NADH-cytochrome c-reductase, kynurenine hydroxylase and fatty acid-CoA ligase.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Disruption of the outer membrane permits proteins in the intermembrane space to leak into the cytosol, leading to cell death.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The outer mitochondrial membrane can associate with the endoplasmic reticulum (ER) membrane, in a structure called MAM (mitochondria-associated ER-membrane).
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] This is important in the ER-mitochondria calcium signaling and is involved in the transfer of lipids between the ER and mitochondria.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Outside the outer membrane are small (diameter: 60 Å) particles named sub-units of Parson.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The **mitochondrial intermembrane space** is the space between the outer membrane and the inner membrane.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] It is also known as perimitochondrial space.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Because the outer membrane is freely permeable to small molecules, the concentrations of small molecules, such as ions and sugars, in the intermembrane space is the same as in the cytosol.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] However, large proteins must have a specific signaling sequence to be transported across the outer membrane, so the protein composition of this space is different from the protein composition of the cytosol.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] One protein that is localized to the intermembrane space in this way is cytochrome c.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] It contains more than 151 different polypeptides, and has a very high protein-to-phospholipid ratio (more than 3:1 by weight, which is about 1 protein for 15 phospholipids).
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The inner membrane is home to around 1/5 of the total protein in a mitochondrion.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Additionally, the inner membrane has an unusual lipid profile, being rich in cardiolipin.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] This phospholipid was originally discovered in cow hearts in 1942, and is usually characteristic of mitochondrial and bacterial plasma membranes.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Cardiolipin contains four fatty acids rather than two, and may help to make the inner membrane impermeable, and its disruption can lead to multiple clinical disorders including neurological disorders and cancer.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Unlike the outer membrane, the inner membrane does not contain porins, and is highly impermeable to all molecules.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Almost all ions and molecules require special membrane transporters to enter or exit the matrix.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Proteins are ferried into the matrix via the translocase of the inner membrane (TIM) complex or via OXA1L.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] In addition, there is a membrane potential across the inner membrane, formed by the action of the enzymes of the electron transport chain.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Inner membrane fusion is mediated by the inner membrane protein OPA1.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The inner mitochondrial membrane is compartmentalized into numerous folds called cristae, which expand the surface area of the inner mitochondrial membrane, enhancing its ability to produce ATP.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] For typical liver mitochondria, the area of the inner membrane is about five times as large as that of the outer membrane.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] This ratio is variable and mitochondria from cells that have a greater demand for ATP, such as muscle cells, contain even more cristae.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Mitochondria within the same cell can have substantially different crista-density, with the ones that are required to produce more energy having much more crista-membrane surface.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] These folds are studded with small round bodies known as F1 particles or oxysomes.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The matrix is the space enclosed by the inner membrane.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] It contains about 2/3 of the total proteins in a mitochondrion.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The matrix is important in the production of ATP with the aid of the ATP synthase contained in the inner membrane.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The matrix contains a highly concentrated mixture of hundreds of enzymes, special mitochondrial ribosomes, tRNA, and several copies of the mitochondrial DNA genome.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Of the enzymes, the major functions include oxidation of pyruvate and fatty acids, and the citric acid cycle.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The DNA molecules are packaged into nucleoids by proteins, one of which is TFAM.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The most prominent roles of mitochondria are to produce the energy currency of the cell, ATP (i.e., phosphorylation of ADP), through respiration and to regulate cellular metabolism.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The central set of reactions involved in ATP production are collectively known as the citric acid cycle, or the Krebs cycle, and oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] However, the mitochondrion has many other functions in addition to the production of ATP.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] A dominant role for the mitochondria is the production of ATP, as reflected by the large number of proteins in the inner membrane for this task.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] This is done by oxidizing the major products of glucose: pyruvate, and NADH, which are produced in the cytosol.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] This type of cellular respiration, known as aerobic respiration, is dependent on the presence of oxygen.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] When oxygen is limited, the glycolytic products will be metabolized by anaerobic fermentation, a process that is independent of the mitochondria.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The production of ATP from glucose and oxygen has an approximately 13-times higher yield during aerobic respiration compared to fermentation.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Plant mitochondria can also produce a limited amount of ATP either by breaking the sugar produced during photosynthesis or without oxygen by using the alternate substrate nitrite.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] ATP crosses out through the inner membrane with the help of a specific protein, and across the outer membrane via porins.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] After conversion of ATP to ADP by dephosphorylation that releases energy, ADP returns via the same route.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] This latter reaction "fills up" the amount of oxaloacetate in the citric acid cycle and is therefore an anaplerotic reaction, increasing the cycle's capacity to metabolize acetyl-CoA when the tissue's energy needs (e.g., in muscle) are suddenly increased by activity.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] In the citric acid cycle, all the intermediates (e.g. citrate, iso-citrate, alpha-ketoglutarate, Succinyl-CoA, succinate, fumarate, malate and oxaloacetate) are regenerated during each turn of the cycle.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Adding more of any of these intermediates to the mitochondrion therefore means that the additional amount is retained within the cycle, increasing all the other intermediates as one is converted into the other.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Hence, the addition of any one of them to the cycle has an anaplerotic effect, and its removal has a cataplerotic effect.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] These anaplerotic and cataplerotic reactions will, during the course of the cycle, increase or decrease the amount of oxaloacetate available to combine with acetyl-CoA to form citric acid.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] This in turn increases or decreases the rate of ATP production by the mitochondrion, and thus the availability of ATP to the cell.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Acetyl-CoA, on the other hand, derived from pyruvate oxidation, or from the beta-oxidation of fatty acids, is the only fuel to enter the citric acid cycle.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] With each turn of the cycle one molecule of acetyl-CoA is consumed for every molecule of oxaloacetate present in the mitochondrial matrix, and is never regenerated.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] It is the oxidation of the acetate portion of acetyl-CoA that produces CO2 and water, with the energy thus released captured in the form of ATP.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] In the liver, the carboxylation of cytosolic pyruvate into intra-mitochondrial oxaloacetate is an early step in the gluconeogenic pathway, which converts lactate and de-aminated alanine into glucose, under the influence of high levels of glucagon and/or epinephrine in the blood.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The enzymes of the citric acid cycle are located in the mitochondrial matrix, with the exception of succinate dehydrogenase, which is bound to the inner mitochondrial membrane as part of Complex II.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The citric acid cycle oxidizes the acetyl-CoA to carbon dioxide, and, in the process, produces reduced cofactors (three molecules of NADH and one molecule of FADH2) that are a source of electrons for the electron transport chain, and a molecule of GTP (which is readily converted to an ATP).
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The electrons from NADH and FADH2 are transferred between multiple coenzymes, and ultimately to oxygen (O2) in several steps via the electron transport chain.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] NADH and FADH2 molecules are produced within the matrix via the citric acid cycle and in the cytoplasm by glycolysis.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Reducing equivalents from the cytoplasm can be imported via the malate-aspartate shuttle system of antiporter proteins or fed into the electron transport chain using a glycerol phosphate shuttle.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The major energy-releasing reactions that make the mitochondrion the "powerhouse of the cell" occur at protein complexes I, III and IV in the inner mitochondrial membrane (NADH dehydrogenase (ubiquinone), cytochrome c reductase, and cytochrome c oxidase).
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] releasing a lot of free energy from the reactants without breaking bonds of an organic fuel.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] While the reactions are controlled by an electron transport chain, free electrons are not amongst the reactants or products in the three reactions shown and therefore do not affect the free energy released, which is used to pump protons (H+) into the intermembrane space.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] This process is efficient, but a small percentage of electrons may prematurely reduce oxygen, forming reactive oxygen species such as superoxide.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] This can cause oxidative stress in the mitochondria and may contribute to the decline in mitochondrial function associated with aging.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] As the proton concentration increases in the intermembrane space, a strong electrochemical gradient is established across the inner membrane.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The protons can return to the matrix through the ATP synthase complex, and their potential energy is used to synthesize ATP from ADP and inorganic phosphate (Pi).
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] This process is called chemiosmosis, and was first described by Peter Mitchell, who was awarded the 1978 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for his work.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Later, part of the 1997 Nobel Prize in Chemistry was awarded to Paul D.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Walker for their clarification of the working mechanism of ATP synthase.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Under certain conditions, protons can re-enter the mitochondrial matrix without contributing to ATP synthesis.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] This process is known as *proton leak* or mitochondrial uncoupling and is due to the facilitated diffusion of protons into the matrix.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The process results in the unharnessed potential energy of the proton electrochemical gradient being released as heat.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The process is mediated by a proton channel called thermogenin, or UCP1.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Thermogenin is primarily found in brown adipose tissue, or brown fat, and is responsible for non-shivering thermogenesis.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Brown adipose tissue is found in mammals, and is at its highest levels in early life and in hibernating animals.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] In humans, brown adipose tissue is present at birth and decreases with age.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Due to heat production, some studies suggested that mitochondria run at a higher temperature.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The internal temperature in mitochondria was previously estimated to be 10C higher than the cytoplasm.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] However, the theory of this remains controversial and disputed as an issue with the sensor, and that temperatures this high would cause damage to mitochondrial components.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Mitochondrial fatty acid synthesis (mtFAS) is essential for cellular respiration and mitochondrial biogenesis.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] In response to mitochondrial acetyl-CoA availability, mtFAS builds acyl chains on the 4'-phosphopantetheine group of the matrix-soluble scaffold protein ACP (holo-ACP), producing acyl-ACP species with varying chain lengths of at least eight carbons.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Among these, octanoyl-ACP (C8) serves as the precursor for lipoic acid biosynthesis.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] In contrast, longer-chain acyl-ACPs (C12–C18) allosterically activate the network of LYRM proteins, which comprises at least 12 members in humans and regulates mitochondrial translation, iron-sulfur cluster biogenesis, and the assembly of electron transport chain complexes.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] MtFAS and ACP thus coordinate the activation of mitochondrial respiration in response to substrate availability.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] This enables cells to increase their oxidative capacity when substrates are abundant and prevents the electron transport chain from running empty and inducing the formation of reactive oxygen species (ROS) under substrate-limited conditions.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] MtFAS is also thought to play a role as a mediator in intracellular signaling due to its influence on the levels of bioactive lipids, such as lysophospholipids and sphingolipids.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The concentrations of free calcium in the cell can regulate an array of reactions and is important for signal transduction in the cell.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Mitochondria can transiently store calcium, a contributing process for the cell's homeostasis of calcium.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Their ability to rapidly take in calcium for later release makes them good "cytosolic buffers" for calcium.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The endoplasmic reticulum (ER) is the most significant storage site of calcium, and there is a significant interplay between the mitochondrion and ER with regard to calcium.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The calcium is taken up into the matrix by the mitochondrial calcium uniporter on the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] It is primarily driven by the mitochondrial membrane potential.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Release of this calcium back into the cell's interior can occur via a sodium-calcium exchange protein or via "calcium-induced-calcium-release" pathways.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] This can initiate calcium spikes or calcium waves with large changes in the membrane potential.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] These can activate a series of second messenger system proteins that can coordinate processes such as neurotransmitter release in nerve cells and release of hormones in endocrine cells.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Ca2+ influx to the mitochondrial matrix has recently been implicated as a mechanism to regulate respiratory bioenergetics by allowing the electrochemical potential across the membrane to transiently "pulse" from ΔΨ-dominated to pH-dominated, facilitating a reduction of oxidative stress.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] In neurons, concomitant increases in cytosolic and mitochondrial calcium act to synchronize neuronal activity with mitochondrial energy metabolism.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Mitochondrial matrix calcium levels can reach the tens of micromolar levels, which is necessary for the activation of isocitrate dehydrogenase, one of the key regulatory enzymes of the Krebs cycle.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The relationship between cellular proliferation and mitochondria has been investigated.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Tumor cells require ample ATP to synthesize bioactive compounds such as lipids, proteins, and nucleotides for rapid proliferation.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The majority of ATP in tumor cells is generated via the oxidative phosphorylation pathway (OxPhos).
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Interference with OxPhos cause cell cycle arrest suggesting that mitochondria play a role in cell proliferation.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Mitochondrial ATP production is also vital for cell division and differentiation in infection in addition to basic functions in the cell including the regulation of cell volume, solute concentration, and cellular architecture.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] ATP levels differ at various stages of the cell cycle suggesting that there is a relationship between the abundance of ATP and the cell's ability to enter a new cell cycle.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] ATP's role in the basic functions of the cell make the cell cycle sensitive to changes in the availability of mitochondrial derived ATP.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The variation in ATP levels at different stages of the cell cycle support the hypothesis that mitochondria play an important role in cell cycle regulation.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Although the specific mechanisms between mitochondria and the cell cycle regulation is not well understood, studies have shown that low energy cell cycle checkpoints monitor the energy capability before committing to another round of cell division.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Programmed cell death (PCD) is crucial for various physiological functions, including organ development and cellular homeostasis.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] It serves as an intrinsic mechanism to prevent malignant transformation and plays a fundamental role in immunity by aiding in antiviral defense, pathogen elimination, inflammation, and immune cell recruitment.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Mitochondria have long been recognized for their central role in the intrinsic pathway of apoptosis, a form of PCD.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] In recent decades, they have also been identified as a signalling hub for much of the innate immune system.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The endosymbiotic origin of mitochondria distinguishes them from other cellular components, and the exposure of mitochondrial elements to the cytosol can trigger the same pathways as infection markers.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] These pathways lead to apoptosis, autophagy, or the induction of proinflammatory genes.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Mitochondria contribute to apoptosis by releasing cytochrome *c*, which directly induces the formation of apoptosomes.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Additionally, they are a source of various damage-associated molecular patterns (DAMPs).
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] These DAMPs are often recognised by the same pattern-recognition receptors (PRRs) that respond to pathogen-associated molecular patterns (PAMPs) during infections.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] For example, mitochondrial mtDNA resembles bacterial DNA due to its lack of CpG methylation and can be detected by Toll-like receptor 9 and cGAS.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Double-stranded RNA (dsRNA), produced due to bidirectional mitochondrial transcription, can activate viral sensing pathways through RIG-I-like receptors.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Additionally, the *N*-formylation of mitochondrial proteins, similar to that of bacterial proteins, can be recognized by formyl peptide receptors.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Normally, these mitochondrial components are sequestered from the rest of the cell but are released following mitochondrial membrane permeabilization during apoptosis or passively after mitochondrial damage.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] However, mitochondria also play an active role in innate immunity, releasing mtDNA in response to metabolic cues.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Mitochondria are also the localization site for immune and apoptosis regulatory proteins, such as BAX, MAVS (located on the outer membrane), and NLRX1 (found in the matrix).
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] These proteins are modulated by the mitochondrial metabolic status and mitochondrial dynamics.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Some cells "donate" mitochondria to other cells.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Such donations occur in multiple cell types, in organisms such as yeast, molluscs, and rodents.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Mitochondrial donation was first observed in 2006.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] As of 2025, it had not been observed in humans *in vivo*.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Donations may occur to help damaged cells, trigger tissue repair or the immune system, or to power distressed cells.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Researchers cultured human mitochondria-free lung cancer cells with stem cells.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The stem cells ejected mitochondria, which were absorbed by the lung cells.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The lung cells then recovered their ability to divide and metabolize glucose.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Mitochondria were then detected moving among lung, heart, brain, fat, bone, and other cells.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Research has not identified how a cell indicates that it needs mitochondrial assistance or how other cells read those indicators.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Various purposes have been observed to explain such donations.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Some mitochondrial functions are performed only in specific types of cells.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] For example, mitochondria in liver cells contain enzymes that allow them to detoxify ammonia, a waste product of protein metabolism.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] A mutation in the genes regulating any of these functions can result in mitochondrial diseases.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Mitochondrial proteins, including those produced from mitochondrial DNA and those imported from the cytoplasm, vary depending on the tissue and the species.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] In humans, 615 distinct types of proteins have been identified from cardiac mitochondria, whereas in rats, 940 proteins have been reported.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The mitochondrial proteome is thought to be dynamically regulated.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Not every function of the mitochondrion is universally conserved in every organism that has it, but some are more commonly kept than the others.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Most make ATP in some way (the vast majority by oxidative phosphorylation; a minority called hydrogenosomes instead use a hydrogenase).
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] All known versions perform iron–sulphur cluster biosynthesis: this is made especially clear by the mitosome, which retains *only* this function.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Also universally kept is the machinery for importing proteins from the cytoplasm into the mitochondrion, without which the mitochondrion cannot function at all.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Mitochondria (or related structures) are found in all eukaryotes (except the Oxymonad *Monocercomonoides*).
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Although commonly depicted as bean-like structures they form a highly dynamic network in the majority of cells where they constantly undergo fission and fusion.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The population of all the mitochondria of a given cell constitutes the **chondriome**.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Mitochondria vary in number and location according to cell type.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] A single mitochondrion is often found in unicellular organisms, while human liver cells have about 1000–2000 mitochondria per cell, making up 1/5 of the cell volume.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The mitochondrial content of otherwise similar cells can vary substantially in size and membrane potential, with differences arising from sources including uneven partitioning at cell division, leading to extrinsic differences in ATP levels and downstream cellular processes.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The mitochondria can be found nestled between myofibrils of muscle or wrapped around the sperm flagellum.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Often, they form a complex 3D branching network inside the cell with the cytoskeleton.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The association with the cytoskeleton determines mitochondrial shape, which can affect the function as well: different structures of the mitochondrial network may afford the population a variety of physical, chemical, and signalling advantages or disadvantages.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Mitochondria in cells are always distributed along microtubules and the distribution of these organelles is also correlated with the endoplasmic reticulum.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Recent evidence suggests that vimentin, one of the components of the cytoskeleton, is also critical to the association with the cytoskeleton.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The mitochondria-associated ER membrane (MAM) is another structural element that is increasingly recognized for its critical role in cellular physiology and homeostasis.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Once considered a technical snag in cell fractionation techniques, the alleged ER vesicle contaminants that invariably appeared in the mitochondrial fraction have been re-identified as membranous structures derived from the MAM—the interface between mitochondria and the ER.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Physical coupling between these two organelles had previously been observed in electron micrographs and has more recently been probed with fluorescence microscopy.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Such studies estimate that at the MAM, which may comprise up to 20% of the mitochondrial outer membrane, the ER and mitochondria are separated by a mere 10–25 nm and held together by protein tethering complexes.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Purified MAM from subcellular fractionation is enriched in enzymes involved in phospholipid exchange, in addition to channels associated with Ca2+ signaling.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] These hints of a prominent role for the MAM in the regulation of cellular lipid stores and signal transduction have been borne out, with significant implications for mitochondrial-associated cellular phenomena, as discussed below.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Not only has the MAM provided insight into the mechanistic basis underlying such physiological processes as intrinsic apoptosis and the propagation of calcium signaling, but it also favors a more refined view of the mitochondria.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The MAM is enriched in enzymes involved in lipid biosynthesis, such as phosphatidylserine synthase on the ER face and phosphatidylserine decarboxylase on the mitochondrial face.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Because mitochondria are dynamic organelles constantly undergoing fission and fusion events, they require a constant and well-regulated supply of phospholipids for membrane integrity.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Such trafficking capacity depends on the MAM, which has been shown to facilitate transfer of lipid intermediates between organelles.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] In contrast to the standard vesicular mechanism of lipid transfer, evidence indicates that the physical proximity of the ER and mitochondrial membranes at the MAM allows for lipid flipping between opposed bilayers.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Despite this unusual and seemingly energetically unfavorable mechanism, such transport does not require ATP.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The MAM may also be part of the secretory pathway, in addition to its role in intracellular lipid trafficking.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] In particular, the MAM appears to be an intermediate destination between the rough ER and the Golgi in the pathway that leads to very-low-density lipoprotein, or VLDL, assembly and secretion.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The MAM thus serves as a critical metabolic and trafficking hub in lipid metabolism.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] But the presence of the MAM resolves this apparent contradiction: the close physical association between the two organelles results in Ca2+ microdomains at contact points that facilitate efficient Ca2+ transmission from the ER to the mitochondria.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Transmission occurs in response to so-called "Ca2+ puffs" generated by spontaneous clustering and activation of IP3R, a canonical ER membrane Ca2+ channel.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The fate of these puffs—in particular, whether they remain restricted to isolated locales or integrated into Ca2+ waves for propagation throughout the cell—is determined in large part by MAM dynamics.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] This Ca2+ tunneling occurs through the low-affinity Ca2+ receptor VDAC1, which recently has been shown to be physically tethered to the IP3R clusters on the ER membrane and enriched at the MAM.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The ability of mitochondria to serve as a Ca2+ sink is a result of the electrochemical gradient generated during oxidative phosphorylation, which makes tunneling of the cation an exergonic process.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Normal, mild calcium influx from cytosol into the mitochondrial matrix causes transient depolarization that is corrected by pumping out protons.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] But transmission of Ca2+ is not unidirectional; rather, it is a two-way street.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The properties of the Ca2+ pump SERCA and the channel IP3R present on the ER membrane facilitate feedback regulation coordinated by MAM function.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] In particular, the clearance of Ca2+ by the MAM allows for spatio-temporal patterning of Ca2+ signaling because Ca2+ alters IP3R activity in a biphasic manner.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] SERCA is likewise affected by mitochondrial feedback: uptake of Ca2+ by the MAM stimulates ATP production, thus providing energy that enables SERCA to reload the ER with Ca2+ for continued Ca2+ efflux at the MAM.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Thus, the MAM is not a passive buffer for Ca2+ puffs; rather it helps modulate further Ca2+ signaling through feedback loops that affect ER dynamics.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Regulating ER release of Ca2+ at the MAM is especially critical because only a certain window of Ca2+ uptake sustains the mitochondria, and consequently the cell, at homeostasis.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Sufficient intraorganelle Ca2+ signaling is required to stimulate metabolism by activating dehydrogenase enzymes critical to flux through the citric acid cycle.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] However, once Ca2+ signaling in the mitochondria passes a certain threshold, it stimulates the intrinsic pathway of apoptosis in part by collapsing the mitochondrial membrane potential required for metabolism.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Given the need for such fine regulation of Ca2+ signaling, it is perhaps unsurprising that dysregulated mitochondrial Ca2+ has been implicated in several neurodegenerative diseases, while the catalogue of tumor suppressors includes a few that are enriched at the MAM.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Recent advances in the identification of the tethers between the mitochondrial and ER membranes suggest that the scaffolding function of the molecular elements involved is secondary to other, non-structural functions.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] In yeast, ERMES, a multiprotein complex of interacting ER- and mitochondrial-resident membrane proteins, is required for lipid transfer at the MAM and exemplifies this principle.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] One of its components, for example, is also a constituent of the protein complex required for insertion of transmembrane beta-barrel proteins into the lipid bilayer.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] However, a homologue of the ERMES complex has not yet been identified in mammalian cells.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Glucose-related protein 75 (grp75) is another dual-function protein.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] In addition to the matrix pool of grp75, a portion serves as a chaperone that physically links the mitochondrial and ER Ca2+ channels VDAC and IP3R for efficient Ca2+ transmission at the MAM.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Another potential tether is Sigma-1R, a non-opioid receptor whose stabilization of ER-resident IP3R may preserve communication at the MAM during the metabolic stress response.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The MAM is a critical signaling, metabolic, and trafficking hub in the cell that allows for the integration of ER and mitochondrial physiology.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Coupling between these organelles is not simply structural but functional as well and critical for overall cellular physiology and homeostasis.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The MAM thus offers a perspective on mitochondria that diverges from the traditional view of this organelle as a static, isolated unit appropriated for its metabolic capacity by the cell.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Instead, this mitochondrial-ER interface emphasizes the integration of the mitochondria, the product of an endosymbiotic event, into diverse cellular processes.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Recently it has also been shown, that mitochondria and MAM-s in neurons are anchored to specialised intercellular communication sites (so called somatic-junctions).
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Microglial processes monitor and protect neuronal functions at these sites, and MAM-s are supposed to have an important role in this type of cellular quality-control.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] There are two hypotheses about the origin of mitochondria: endosymbiotic and autogenous.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The endosymbiotic hypothesis suggests that mitochondria were originally prokaryotic cells, capable of implementing oxidative mechanisms that were not possible for eukaryotic cells; they became endosymbionts living inside the eukaryote.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] In the autogenous hypothesis, mitochondria were born by splitting off a portion of DNA from the nucleus of the eukaryotic cell at the time of divergence with the prokaryotes; this DNA portion would have been enclosed by membranes, which could not be crossed by proteins.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] Since mitochondria have many features in common with bacteria, the endosymbiotic hypothesis is the more widely accepted of the two accounts.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] A mitochondrion contains DNA, which is organized as several copies of a single, usually circular chromosome.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] This mitochondrial chromosome contains genes for redox proteins, such as those of the respiratory chain.
[src:cell-biology/mitochondrion-p01] The CoRR hypothesis proposes that this co-location is required for redox regulation.
